{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_7O2XlxoY5BpabkDLVgJQTfFN","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Live prod scenarios\n2\t\n3\tTwo high-complexity, end-to-end scenarios that exercise the **system spaces** (`system-appbuilder`,\n4\t`system-architect`, `system-research`, `system-store`, `system-engineer`) and the **unified event\n5\tpipeline** through the **THING agent**, against the **live production cluster and a live LLM**.\n6\t\n7\tEvery scenario runs as a real user would: a disposable prod test user, a real compute pod, a real\n8\tTHING chat session, real model calls. Nothing is mocked. If a scenario passes, the feature works in\n9\tproduction — not in a unit test.\n10\t\n11\t| # | Scenario | Covers |\n12\t|---|---|---|\n13\t| [05](./05-latam/scenario.md) | **Latin America** — six months, nine countries, one growing project | the full lifecycle: incremental space growth, integrations, a THING-controlled **project app** automating bookings/transport/notifications, live in the project web app |\n14\t| [06](./06-tanzania/scenario.md) | **Tanzania trip** — one attachment becomes spaces + a live, updatable app | file ingest (`system-files`); per-leg spaces; live-project app (`writeProjectTable`/`Page`/`Api` + rows seed); `db:write` later-update; compound + multilingual ask |\n15\t\n16\t## Running one\n17\t\n18\t```bash\n19\tcd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\n20\tnode smoke.mjs                 # prove the harness + prod are healthy first (≈1 min)\n21\tnode ../05-latam/run.mjs        # a scenario's runner writes its own report\n22\t```\n23\t\n24\tEach scenario directory holds a `scenario.md` (the spec) and a `run.mjs` (the executable spec), and\n25\twrites `sdk/org/scenarios/<id>/results/report.md` plus a raw trace JSON. The **Actual results**\n26\tsection of `scenario.md` is pasted back from that report, so the document is both the plan and the\n27\trecord.\n28\t\n29\t## Authoring a new scenario — the format + the workflow\n30\t\n31\tThe full **format** (the six-section `scenario.md` structure, the feature catalog, the validation\n32\tprocess, the harness API) and the **workflow** (run → triage → fix-in-product-with-a-test →\n33\tverify-live → report, plus the image-rebuild loop and multi-hour babysitting discipline) now live,\n34\tself-contained, in the automation instance that drives this campaign:\n35\t[`automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md`](../../../automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md)\n36\t(run it with `node automation/lmauto.mjs run scenario-campaign`).\n37\t\n38\tTo author one by hand, copy the template:\n39\t\n40\t- **[`_template/`](./_template/)** — `cp -r _template <NN-slug>`, then fill **`<NN-slug>/scenario.md`**\n41\t  (the six-section spec with a feature checklist) and **`run.mjs`** (the runner\n42\t  scaffold — checkpoint/resume, keepalive, resilient send, scripted asks, and attachment + live-app +\n43\t  signed-inbound helpers all pre-wired; replace the `SCENARIO_*` config and write the Acts).\n44\t\n45\tTo start: `cp -r _template 07-myscenario`, then fill `07-myscenario/scenario.md` and `run.mjs`.\n46\t\n47\t**Quick start:**\n48\t```bash\n49\tcd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\n50\tnode smoke.mjs                       # prove the harness + prod are healthy (≈1 min)\n51\tnode ../07-myscenario/run.mjs        # run it; writes 07-myscenario/results/report.md\n52\t```\n53\t\n54\t## The harness\n55\t\n56\t`harness/` is zero-dependency Node ESM. It drives the pod's HTTP API directly — no browser needed —\n57\tbecause the pod exposes the whole surface the `/chat` SPA uses (`sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/`):\n58\t\n59\t```js\n60\timport { getUser } from './provision.mjs';            // register → pod → Azure keys → ready\n61\timport { Pod } from './lib/pod.mjs';                  // projects, files, store, hooks, inbound, app\n62\timport { ThingSession, approveAllConsent } from './lib/thing.mjs';\n63\timport { Report } from './lib/report.mjs';            // → the markdown results table\n64\t\n65\tconst user = await getUser('my-scenario');\n66\tconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\n67\tconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { onAsk: approveAllConsent, verbose: true });\n68\tawait thing.start();                                   // POST /api/sessions  (interactive!)\n69\tconst turn = await thing.send('install a slack integration and watch #eng');\n70\t\n71\tturn.delegates;      // ['system-store/finder/…', 'system-appbuilder/automator/…']\n72\tturn.yields;         // every global THING called, incl. installSpace\n73\tturn.tokens;         // { in, out }\n74\tthing.consentCards() // every ConsentCard raised, and how it was answered\n75\t```\n76\t\n77\t### Why assertions read the trace, not the prose\n78\t\n79\tThe pod streams the full execution trace (`libs/core/src/sandbox/trace.ts`), so a scenario asserts on\n80\twhat the agent **did** — which specialist it delegated to, which consent-marked global it called,\n81\twhich yields resolved, which hooks fired, how many tokens it burned — instead of grading a paragraph\n82\tof English. A scenario that only checks the final message is a scenario that passes when the system\n83\tis broken.\n84\t\n85\t### Things the harness learned the hard way\n86\t\n87\t- **Consent needs an interactive session.** The consent prompter is only wired when\n88\t  `POST /api/sessions` created the session. Headless paths (hooks, delegates, webhook dispatch) have\n89\t  no prompter and **fail closed** — that is the designed behaviour (a scenario should assert it, not work around it).\n90\t- **`PUT /api/compute/env` rolls the pod, and sessions are in-memory.** A session created against\n91\t  the old replica dies with it (`404 unknown session`). `provisionUser()` therefore loads env\n92\t  *before* the first turn, skips the PUT when nothing changed, and then proves a session survives\n93\t  before handing the pod over (`waitPodSettled`).\n94\t- **`pod.ready` is `readyReplicas > 0`**, which is true throughout a rolling update and precedes\n95\t  Envoy wiring the new endpoint. Never treat it as \"my next request will land on the new pod\".\n96\t- **The gateway JWT secret is double-base64.** `.data.GATEWAY_JWT_SECRET` in k8s decodes to the env\n97\t  *value*, which is itself base64 of the signing key. Decode once when fetching, once when signing.\n98\t\n99\t## Budget\n100\t\n101\tScenarios burn real tokens. `provisionUser()` loads the **direct Azure** keys from `sdk/org/.env`\n102\tinto the pod env, so agent traffic bypasses the per-user LiteLLM key that carries the tier budget —\n103\ta run cannot be halted by a tier cap mid-scenario. If a pod ever is capped, provision a new user\n104\t(`node provision.mjs <label>`) and re-run; test users are disposable by design.\n105\t\n106\tTest users are named `<label>-<base36-ts>@lmthing.test` and each gets its own `user-<id>` namespace\n107\tand pod. Clean up with `kubectl delete ns user-<id>`.\n108\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f21d2fda-94ab-442d-8f32-017580283d3b","uuid":"8c3c7f29-9849-43a4-bb5a-1c273307b8b0","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:53:17.039Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/README.md","content":"# Live prod scenarios\n\nTwo high-complexity, end-to-end scenarios that exercise the **system spaces** (`system-appbuilder`,\n`system-architect`, `system-research`, `system-store`, `system-engineer`) and the **unified event\npipeline** through the **THING agent**, against the **live production cluster and a live LLM**.\n\nEvery scenario runs as a real user would: a disposable prod test user, a real compute pod, a real\nTHING chat session, real model calls. Nothing is mocked. If a scenario passes, the feature works in\nproduction — not in a unit test.\n\n| # | Scenario | Covers |\n|---|---|---|\n| [05](./05-latam/scenario.md) | **Latin America** — six months, nine countries, one growing project | the full lifecycle: incremental space growth, integrations, a THING-controlled **project app** automating bookings/transport/notifications, live in the project web app |\n| [06](./06-tanzania/scenario.md) | **Tanzania trip** — one attachment becomes spaces + a live, updatable app | file ingest (`system-files`); per-leg spaces; live-project app (`writeProjectTable`/`Page`/`Api` + rows seed); `db:write` later-update; compound + multilingual ask |\n\n## Running one\n\n```bash\ncd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\nnode smoke.mjs                 # prove the harness + prod are healthy first (≈1 min)\nnode ../05-latam/run.mjs        # a scenario's runner writes its own report\n```\n\nEach scenario directory holds a `scenario.md` (the spec) and a `run.mjs` (the executable spec), and\nwrites `sdk/org/scenarios/<id>/results/report.md` plus a raw trace JSON. The **Actual results**\nsection of `scenario.md` is pasted back from that report, so the document is both the plan and the\nrecord.\n\n## Authoring a new scenario — the format + the workflow\n\nThe full **format** (the six-section `scenario.md` structure, the feature catalog, the validation\nprocess, the harness API) and the **workflow** (run → triage → fix-in-product-with-a-test →\nverify-live → report, plus the image-rebuild loop and multi-hour babysitting discipline) now live,\nself-contained, in the automation instance that drives this campaign:\n[`automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md`](../../../automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md)\n(run it with `node automation/lmauto.mjs run scenario-campaign`).\n\nTo author one by hand, copy the template:\n\n- **[`_template/`](./_template/)** — `cp -r _template <NN-slug>`, then fill **`<NN-slug>/scenario.md`**\n  (the six-section spec with a feature checklist) and **`run.mjs`** (the runner\n  scaffold — checkpoint/resume, keepalive, resilient send, scripted asks, and attachment + live-app +\n  signed-inbound helpers all pre-wired; replace the `SCENARIO_*` config and write the Acts).\n\nTo start: `cp -r _template 07-myscenario`, then fill `07-myscenario/scenario.md` and `run.mjs`.\n\n**Quick start:**\n```bash\ncd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\nnode smoke.mjs                       # prove the harness + prod are healthy (≈1 min)\nnode ../07-myscenario/run.mjs        # run it; writes 07-myscenario/results/report.md\n```\n\n## The harness\n\n`harness/` is zero-dependency Node ESM. It drives the pod's HTTP API directly — no browser needed —\nbecause the pod exposes the whole surface the `/chat` SPA uses (`sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/`):\n\n```js\nimport { getUser } from './provision.mjs';            // register → pod → Azure keys → ready\nimport { Pod } from './lib/pod.mjs';                  // projects, files, store, hooks, inbound, app\nimport { ThingSession, approveAllConsent } from './lib/thing.mjs';\nimport { Report } from './lib/report.mjs';            // → the markdown results table\n\nconst user = await getUser('my-scenario');\nconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\nconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { onAsk: approveAllConsent, verbose: true });\nawait thing.start();                                   // POST /api/sessions  (interactive!)\nconst turn = await thing.send('install a slack integration and watch #eng');\n\nturn.delegates;      // ['system-store/finder/…', 'system-appbuilder/automator/…']\nturn.yields;         // every global THING called, incl. installSpace\nturn.tokens;         // { in, out }\nthing.consentCards() // every ConsentCard raised, and how it was answered\n```\n\n### Why assertions read the trace, not the prose\n\nThe pod streams the full execution trace (`libs/core/src/sandbox/trace.ts`), so a scenario asserts on\nwhat the agent **did** — which specialist it delegated to, which consent-marked global it called,\nwhich yields resolved, which hooks fired, how many tokens it burned — instead of grading a paragraph\nof English. A scenario that only checks the final message is a scenario that passes when the system\nis broken.\n\n### Things the harness learned the hard way\n\n- **Consent needs an interactive session.** The consent prompter is only wired when\n  `POST /api/sessions` created the session. Headless paths (hooks, delegates, webhook dispatch) have\n  no prompter and **fail closed** — that is the designed behaviour (a scenario should assert it, not work around it).\n- **`PUT /api/compute/env` rolls the pod, and sessions are in-memory.** A session created against\n  the old replica dies with it (`404 unknown session`). `provisionUser()` therefore loads env\n  *before* the first turn, skips the PUT when nothing changed, and then proves a session survives\n  before handing the pod over (`waitPodSettled`).\n- **`pod.ready` is `readyReplicas > 0`**, which is true throughout a rolling update and precedes\n  Envoy wiring the new endpoint. Never treat it as \"my next request will land on the new pod\".\n- **The gateway JWT secret is double-base64.** `.data.GATEWAY_JWT_SECRET` in k8s decodes to the env\n  *value*, which is itself base64 of the signing key. Decode once when fetching, once when signing.\n\n## Budget\n\nScenarios burn real tokens. `provisionUser()` loads the **direct Azure** keys from `sdk/org/.env`\ninto the pod env, so agent traffic bypasses the per-user LiteLLM key that carries the tier budget —\na run cannot be halted by a tier cap mid-scenario. If a pod ever is capped, provision a new user\n(`node provision.mjs <label>`) and re-run; test users are disposable by design.\n\nTest users are named `<label>-<base36-ts>@lmthing.test` and each gets its own `user-<id>` namespace\nand pod. Clean up with `kubectl delete ns user-<id>`.\n","numLines":108,"startLine":1,"totalLines":108}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_VZn3hZ5cgNjVOdovDO74KDje","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t#!/usr/bin/env node\n2\t/**\n3\t * Scenario runner TEMPLATE — copy this to `sdk/org/scenarios/<id>/run.mjs` and fill in the Acts.\n4\t * It bakes in every hardening pattern the campaigns learned the hard way (see the harness API +\n5\t * hardening patterns in automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md): per-Act\n6\t * checkpointing + resume, a keepalive pinger, a resilient `send`\n7\t * that survives a full pod restart, a scripted ask answerer, attachment + live-app + inbound helpers,\n8\t * and trace-based assertions.\n9\t *\n10\t * NOTE: `ThingSession` now self-heals SESSION EVICTION natively (a long turn's sub-sessions can push\n11\t * a small pod past MAX_SESSIONS): pullEvents treats a post-work 404 as turn-complete, and it\n12\t * re-establishes an evicted session before the next send. The `thing.send` wrapper below is the extra\n13\t * belt for a FULL pod roll/restart. For a session-heavy scenario, also raise the cap on the test pod:\n14\t *   ssh … 'kubectl set env deployment/lmthing MAX_SESSIONS=25 -n user-<id>'\n15\t *\n16\t *   cd sdk/org/scenarios/harness && node ../<id>/run.mjs [--acts=1,2,3] [--fresh]\n17\t *\n18\t * Replace every `SCENARIO_*` below, then write your Acts where marked.\n19\t */\n20\timport { existsSync, mkdirSync, readFileSync, writeFileSync } from 'node:fs';\n21\timport { createHmac } from 'node:crypto';\n22\timport { getUser } from '../harness/provision.mjs';\n23\timport { Pod } from '../harness/lib/pod.mjs';\n24\timport { ThingSession } from '../harness/lib/thing.mjs';\n25\timport { Report } from '../harness/lib/report.mjs';\n26\timport { mergePodEnv, waitPodReady, waitPodSettled } from '../harness/lib/gateway.mjs';\n27\timport { SDK_ORG } from '../harness/lib/paths.mjs';\n28\t\n29\t// ── config — EDIT THESE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n30\tconst ID = 'SCENARIO_ID'; // e.g. '06-something'\n31\tconst TITLE = 'SCENARIO_TITLE';\n32\tconst LABEL = 'SCENARIO_LABEL'; // provision.mjs label (disposable user prefix)\n33\tconst PROJECT = 'SCENARIO_PROJECT'; // the project id the scenario runs in ('user' = default)\n34\t/** Any integration/env secrets the scenario needs, loaded BEFORE the first session. */\n35\tconst POD_ENV = {\n36\t  // INTEGRATION_DEMO_BASE_URL: 'https://httpbin.org/anything',\n37\t  // INTEGRATION_DEMO_API_TOKEN: 'demo-token',\n38\t  // INTEGRATION_DEMO_WEBHOOK_SECRET: 'demo-hmac-secret',\n39\t};\n40\t\n41\tconst RESULTS = `${SDK_ORG}/scenarios/${ID}/results`;\n42\tconst CHECKPOINT = `${RESULTS}/checkpoint.json`;\n43\tconst argActs = (process.argv.find((a) => a.startsWith('--acts=')) ?? '').slice(7);\n44\tconst ACTS = argActs ? argActs.split(',').map(Number) : [1, 2, 3, 4];\n45\tconst FRESH = process.argv.includes('--fresh');\n46\tconst sleep = (ms) => new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, ms));\n47\tconst now = () => Date.now();\n48\t\n49\t// ── checkpoint (resume from the last good Act) ──────────────────────────────────\n50\tfunction loadCheckpoint() {\n51\t  if (FRESH || !existsSync(CHECKPOINT)) return { acts: {}, sessionId: null };\n52\t  try { return JSON.parse(readFileSync(CHECKPOINT, 'utf8')); } catch { return { acts: {}, sessionId: null }; }\n53\t}\n54\tfunction saveCheckpoint(cp) {\n55\t  mkdirSync(RESULTS, { recursive: true });\n56\t  writeFileSync(CHECKPOINT, JSON.stringify(cp, null, 2));\n57\t  console.log(`\\n💾 checkpoint → ${CHECKPOINT}`);\n58\t}\n59\t\n60\t// ── scripted asks: approve/deny consent, settle any other ask so a run never hangs ──\n61\tconst scriptedOnAsk = (consent) => (d) => {\n62\t  if (d?.type === 'ConsentCard') return consent;\n63\t  if (d?.type) return {}; // settle Forms/other asks with an empty submission\n64\t  return undefined;\n65\t};\n66\t\n67\t// ── signed inbound helper (a provider-shaped, HMAC-signed webhook to the pod) ────\n68\tfunction signedInbound(pod, path, body, secret, header = 'x-demo-signature') {\n69\t  const raw = typeof body === 'string' ? body : JSON.stringify(body);\n70\t  const sig = 'sha256=' + createHmac('sha256', secret).update(raw).digest('hex');\n71\t  return pod.inbound(path, raw, { [header]: sig });\n72\t}\n73\t\n74\t// ── fixture-token assertion (the ONLY proof a fixture was actually READ) ────────\n75\t// Each fixture in fixtures/links.md carries a token that appears in that file and NOWHERE else.\n76\t// A token in the chat reply proves nothing — the model can guess. A token in a DB ROW or a SPACE\n77\t// FILE proves the bytes were ingested: the image through vision, the audio through transcription,\n78\t// the pdf/xlsx through readDocument. Assert every fixture this way, or it is dead weight.\n79\tasync function assertTokenInState(report, pod, projectId, { fixture, token, tables = [], spaces = true }) {\n80\t  const rx = new RegExp(token.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\\]\\\\]/g, '\\\\$&'), 'i');\n81\t  const hits = [];\n82\t  const manifest = await pod.appManifest(projectId).catch(() => ({}));\n83\t  const names = (manifest?.tables ?? []).map((t) => (typeof t === 'string' ? t : t.name));\n84\t  for (const name of tables.length ? tables : names) {\n85\t    const rows = (await pod.appData(projectId, name).catch(() => ({ rows: [] }))).rows ?? [];\n86\t    if (rows.some((r) => rx.test(JSON.stringify(r)))) hits.push(`db:${name}`);\n87\t  }\n88\t  if (spaces && !hits.length) {\n89\t    const tree = await pod.fsTree().catch(() => null);\n90\t    const files = JSON.stringify(tree ?? '');\n91\t    if (rx.test(files)) hits.push('space-file');\n92\t  }\n93\t  report.check(\n94\t    `${fixture}: its unique token \"${token}\" landed in REAL STATE (not prose)`,\n95\t    hits.length > 0,\n96\t    hits.length ? hits.join(', ') : 'NOT FOUND in any row or space file — the file was never read',\n97\t  );\n98\t  return hits;\n99\t}\n100\t\n101\t// ── the app's OWN api routes — the layer the USER actually sees ─────────────────\n102\t// A dashboard can render 0 / €0.00 on every tile while /app/data/<table> happily returns all its\n103\t// rows, because the page's own aggregation route 500s. That really happened. Assert the routes the\n104\t// PAGES fetch, not just the raw data API.\n105\tasync function assertAppApi(report, pod, projectId, routes = []) {\n106\t  for (const [route, check] of Object.entries(routes)) {\n107\t    const res = await pod.appApi(projectId, route, undefined, 'GET').catch((e) => ({ status: 0, body: String(e) }));\n108\t    const ok = res.status === 200 && (typeof check === 'function' ? check(res.body) : true);\n109\t    report.check(`app's own route GET /${projectId}/api/${route} → 200 + real data`, ok, `status ${res.status}: ${JSON.stringify(res.body).slice(0, 160)}`);\n110\t  }\n111\t}\n112\t\n113\t// ── project-app assertion helper (build + read real rows) ────────────────────────\n114\t// A real live-project app: compile it and confirm real assets came out, then read its DB rows.\n115\t// (`built` lives at manifest.build.built and only reflects the LAST compile — so build explicitly\n116\t//  and read the POST result, which carries assetManifest + routes — see the harness gotchas in the campaign prompt.)\n117\tasync function assertLiveApp(report, pod, projectId, { minRowTables = {} } = {}) {\n118\t  const build = await pod.appBuild(projectId).catch((e) => ({ built: false, error: String(e) }));\n119\t  const assets = build?.assetManifest ?? [];\n120\t  report.check('app compiles (built:true) with real JS assets', build?.built === true && assets.some((a) => /\\.js$/.test(a)), JSON.stringify({ built: build?.built, assets }).slice(0, 200));\n121\t  report.check('app serves ≥1 page route', (build?.routes?.length ?? 0) >= 1, (build?.routes ?? []).map((x) => x.routePath).join(', '));\n122\t  const page = await pod.appPage(projectId).catch((e) => ({ status: 0, body: String(e) }));\n123\t  report.check(`/app/${projectId}/ serves 200 HTML`, page.status === 200 && String(page.body).includes('<!doctype'), `status ${page.status}, ${String(page.body).length} bytes`);\n124\t  // minRowTables: { <table-regex>: <min rows> } — assert real data landed (moved into the db).\n125\t  const manifest = await pod.appManifest(projectId).catch(() => ({}));\n126\t  const names = (manifest?.tables ?? []).map((t) => (typeof t === 'string' ? t : t.name));\n127\t  for (const [rx, min] of Object.entries(minRowTables)) {\n128\t    const t = names.find((n) => new RegExp(rx, 'i').test(n));\n129\t    const rows = t ? (await pod.appData(projectId, t).catch(() => ({ rows: [] }))).rows ?? [] : [];\n130\t    report.check(`table /${rx}/ has ≥${min} rows`, rows.length >= min, `${t ?? '(none)'}: ${rows.length} rows`);\n131\t  }\n132\t  return build;\n133\t}\n134\t\n135\t// ── main ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n136\tconst report = new Report(ID, TITLE);\n137\tconst cp = loadCheckpoint();\n138\tconst t0 = now();\n139\t\n140\tconst user = await getUser(LABEL);\n141\tconsole.log(`user ${user.email} (${user.userId}) → ${user.pod}`);\n142\t\n143\tconst { changed } = await mergePodEnv(user.token, POD_ENV);\n144\tif (changed) { await waitPodReady(user.token); await waitPodSettled(user.token); }\n145\t\n146\tconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\n147\tconst projects = await pod.listProjects();\n148\tif (PROJECT !== 'user' && !(projects.projects ?? []).some((p) => (p.id ?? p) === PROJECT)) {\n149\t  await pod.createProject(PROJECT);\n150\t}\n151\tcp.projectId = PROJECT;\n152\tcp.user = { label: LABEL, email: user.email, userId: user.userId };\n153\t\n154\tconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { projectId: PROJECT, onAsk: scriptedOnAsk(true), verbose: true });\n155\tif (cp.sessionId && !FRESH) {\n156\t  try { await thing.resume(cp.sessionId); } catch { cp.sessionId = await thing.start(); }\n157\t} else {\n158\t  cp.sessionId = await thing.start();\n159\t}\n160\tsaveCheckpoint(cp);\n161\t\n162\t// keep the pod warm so an idle scale-to-zero never kills the session mid-run\n163\tconst keepalive = setInterval(() => {\n164\t  pod.req('POST', '/api/keepalive', {}).catch(() => pod.req('POST', '/api/compute/wake', {}).catch(() => {}));\n165\t}, 30_000);\n166\tkeepalive.unref?.();\n167\t\n168\t// resilient send: survive a pod roll/restart (also exercises the auto-resume edge)\n169\tconst _send = thing.send.bind(thing);\n170\tthing.send = async (content, opts = {}) => {\n171\t  for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n172\t    try { return await _send(content, opts); }\n173\t    catch (e) {\n174\t      const msg = String(e?.body?.error ?? e?.message ?? '');\n175\t      const lost = e?.status === 404 || /unknown session|404/.test(msg);\n176\t      const errored = /entered error state/.test(msg);\n177\t      if ((!lost && !errored) || attempt >= 3) throw e;\n178\t      await waitPodReady(user.token).catch(() => {});\n179\t      for (let i = 0; i < 40; i++) { if (await pod.listProjects().then(() => true).catch(() => false)) break; await sleep(4_000); }\n180\t      if (lost && !errored) { try { await thing.resume(cp.sessionId); continue; } catch { /* fresh */ } }\n181\t      cp.sessionId = await thing.start(); saveCheckpoint(cp);\n182\t    }\n183\t  }\n184\t};\n185\t\n186\tconst metrics = { tokens: { in: 0, out: 0 } };\n187\tconst acc = (turn) => { metrics.tokens.in += turn.tokens.in; metrics.tokens.out += turn.tokens.out; return turn; };\n188\t\n189\t// ═══ ACT I ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n190\tif (ACTS.includes(1)) {\n191\t  report.step('Act I — <name>', '<the contract this Act asserts>');\n192\t  const t = acc(await thing.send('<the user message>', { timeoutMs: 900_000 }));\n193\t  report.check('no eval/typecheck errors', t.errors.length === 0, JSON.stringify(t.errors).slice(0, 200));\n194\t  // report.check('delegated to <space>', thing.didDelegate('<space>'), t.delegates.join(', '));\n195\t  // ...assert on the trace + real side effects (files/rows/spaces), not the prose...\n196\t  cp.acts.I = { passed: report.passed };\n197\t  saveCheckpoint(cp);\n198\t}\n199\t\n200\t// ═══ ACT II / III / IV — same shape; gate each on ACTS.includes(n) + checkpoint ═══\n201\t// (Toggle scripted consent for a deny branch: thing.onAsk = scriptedOnAsk(false); ... reset to true.)\n202\t//\n203\t// ── Example: a file attachment → a live app with the data seeded in (the S06 pattern) ──\n204\t// const attachment = await pod.upload(`${SDK_ORG}/scenarios/${ID}/fixtures/notes.md`);\n205\t// report.check('file uploaded (kind=file)', attachment.kind === 'file', attachment.mediaType);\n206\t// // Attachments ride the WS path (HTTP /message drops them). THING hands the file to a specialist\n207\t// // via attachmentIds; the automator readDocument()s it and seeds rows via writeProjectTable(...,rows).\n208\t// const t = acc(await thing.sendWithAttachments('<the user message>', [attachment], { timeoutMs: 1_500_000 }));\n209\t// report.check('read the file (system-files)', thing.didDelegate('system-files'), t.delegates.join(', '));\n210\t// await assertLiveApp(report, pod, PROJECT, { minRowTables: { 'flight|itinerary': 5, 'accommodation|hotel': 6 } });\n211\t//\n212\t// ── Example: a LATER update changes the db (use a NEW fact NOT already in any seed) ──\n213\t// const before = JSON.stringify(await pod.appData(PROJECT, '<table>').catch(() => ({})));\n214\t// acc(await thing.send('Mark X as done and record confirmation \"NEW-TOKEN-123\".', { timeoutMs: 900_000 }));\n215\t// await sleep(4_000);\n216\t// const after = JSON.stringify(await pod.appData(PROJECT, '<table>').catch(() => ({})));\n217\t// report.check('the NEW fact landed in the db', !before.includes('new-token-123') && after.toLowerCase().includes('new-token-123'), 'before/after diff');\n218\t//\n219\t// ── Example: a signed inbound webhook fires a code-handler hook (0 LLM) ──\n220\t// const res = await signedInbound(pod, 'demo', { message: { message_id: 1, text: 'TIP: hello', chat: { id: 'c1' }, from: { id: 'u1' } } }, POD_ENV.INTEGRATION_DEMO_WEBHOOK_SECRET);\n221\t// report.check('inbound accepted (verify→emit)', res.status === 200 && res.body?.events >= 1, JSON.stringify(res.body));\n222\t\n223\t// ═══ verdict ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n224\tconst stats = thing.stats();\n225\treport.step('Whole-session invariants', 'no eval/typecheck errors; routing not degraded over the run');\n226\treport.check('zero eval/typecheck errors across the session', stats.errors === 0, `${stats.errors} errors`);\n227\treport.metric('wall clock', ((now() - t0) / 60_000).toFixed(1), ' min');\n228\treport.metric('total tokens (in/out)', `${metrics.tokens.in} / ${metrics.tokens.out}`);\n229\t\n230\treport.save(`${RESULTS}/report.md`);\n231\treport.saveTrace(`${RESULTS}/trace.json`, thing);\n232\tcp.done = true; cp.summary = report.summary(); saveCheckpoint(cp);\n233\tconsole.log(JSON.stringify(report.summary(), null, 2));\n234\tprocess.exit(report.passed ? 0 : 1);\n235\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f21d2fda-94ab-442d-8f32-017580283d3b","uuid":"33e02091-fee3-4d11-86d8-b702376f3eaa","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:53:17.041Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/_template/run.mjs","content":"#!/usr/bin/env node\n/**\n * Scenario runner TEMPLATE — copy this to `sdk/org/scenarios/<id>/run.mjs` and fill in the Acts.\n * It bakes in every hardening pattern the campaigns learned the hard way (see the harness API +\n * hardening patterns in automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md): per-Act\n * checkpointing + resume, a keepalive pinger, a resilient `send`\n * that survives a full pod restart, a scripted ask answerer, attachment + live-app + inbound helpers,\n * and trace-based assertions.\n *\n * NOTE: `ThingSession` now self-heals SESSION EVICTION natively (a long turn's sub-sessions can push\n * a small pod past MAX_SESSIONS): pullEvents treats a post-work 404 as turn-complete, and it\n * re-establishes an evicted session before the next send. The `thing.send` wrapper below is the extra\n * belt for a FULL pod roll/restart. For a session-heavy scenario, also raise the cap on the test pod:\n *   ssh … 'kubectl set env deployment/lmthing MAX_SESSIONS=25 -n user-<id>'\n *\n *   cd sdk/org/scenarios/harness && node ../<id>/run.mjs [--acts=1,2,3] [--fresh]\n *\n * Replace every `SCENARIO_*` below, then write your Acts where marked.\n */\nimport { existsSync, mkdirSync, readFileSync, writeFileSync } from 'node:fs';\nimport { createHmac } from 'node:crypto';\nimport { getUser } from '../harness/provision.mjs';\nimport { Pod } from '../harness/lib/pod.mjs';\nimport { ThingSession } from '../harness/lib/thing.mjs';\nimport { Report } from '../harness/lib/report.mjs';\nimport { mergePodEnv, waitPodReady, waitPodSettled } from '../harness/lib/gateway.mjs';\nimport { SDK_ORG } from '../harness/lib/paths.mjs';\n\n// ── config — EDIT THESE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nconst ID = 'SCENARIO_ID'; // e.g. '06-something'\nconst TITLE = 'SCENARIO_TITLE';\nconst LABEL = 'SCENARIO_LABEL'; // provision.mjs label (disposable user prefix)\nconst PROJECT = 'SCENARIO_PROJECT'; // the project id the scenario runs in ('user' = default)\n/** Any integration/env secrets the scenario needs, loaded BEFORE the first session. */\nconst POD_ENV = {\n  // INTEGRATION_DEMO_BASE_URL: 'https://httpbin.org/anything',\n  // INTEGRATION_DEMO_API_TOKEN: 'demo-token',\n  // INTEGRATION_DEMO_WEBHOOK_SECRET: 'demo-hmac-secret',\n};\n\nconst RESULTS = `${SDK_ORG}/scenarios/${ID}/results`;\nconst CHECKPOINT = `${RESULTS}/checkpoint.json`;\nconst argActs = (process.argv.find((a) => a.startsWith('--acts=')) ?? '').slice(7);\nconst ACTS = argActs ? argActs.split(',').map(Number) : [1, 2, 3, 4];\nconst FRESH = process.argv.includes('--fresh');\nconst sleep = (ms) => new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, ms));\nconst now = () => Date.now();\n\n// ── checkpoint (resume from the last good Act) ──────────────────────────────────\nfunction loadCheckpoint() {\n  if (FRESH || !existsSync(CHECKPOINT)) return { acts: {}, sessionId: null };\n  try { return JSON.parse(readFileSync(CHECKPOINT, 'utf8')); } catch { return { acts: {}, sessionId: null }; }\n}\nfunction saveCheckpoint(cp) {\n  mkdirSync(RESULTS, { recursive: true });\n  writeFileSync(CHECKPOINT, JSON.stringify(cp, null, 2));\n  console.log(`\\n💾 checkpoint → ${CHECKPOINT}`);\n}\n\n// ── scripted asks: approve/deny consent, settle any other ask so a run never hangs ──\nconst scriptedOnAsk = (consent) => (d) => {\n  if (d?.type === 'ConsentCard') return consent;\n  if (d?.type) return {}; // settle Forms/other asks with an empty submission\n  return undefined;\n};\n\n// ── signed inbound helper (a provider-shaped, HMAC-signed webhook to the pod) ────\nfunction signedInbound(pod, path, body, secret, header = 'x-demo-signature') {\n  const raw = typeof body === 'string' ? body : JSON.stringify(body);\n  const sig = 'sha256=' + createHmac('sha256', secret).update(raw).digest('hex');\n  return pod.inbound(path, raw, { [header]: sig });\n}\n\n// ── fixture-token assertion (the ONLY proof a fixture was actually READ) ────────\n// Each fixture in fixtures/links.md carries a token that appears in that file and NOWHERE else.\n// A token in the chat reply proves nothing — the model can guess. A token in a DB ROW or a SPACE\n// FILE proves the bytes were ingested: the image through vision, the audio through transcription,\n// the pdf/xlsx through readDocument. Assert every fixture this way, or it is dead weight.\nasync function assertTokenInState(report, pod, projectId, { fixture, token, tables = [], spaces = true }) {\n  const rx = new RegExp(token.replace(/[.*+?^${}()|[\\]\\\\]/g, '\\\\$&'), 'i');\n  const hits = [];\n  const manifest = await pod.appManifest(projectId).catch(() => ({}));\n  const names = (manifest?.tables ?? []).map((t) => (typeof t === 'string' ? t : t.name));\n  for (const name of tables.length ? tables : names) {\n    const rows = (await pod.appData(projectId, name).catch(() => ({ rows: [] }))).rows ?? [];\n    if (rows.some((r) => rx.test(JSON.stringify(r)))) hits.push(`db:${name}`);\n  }\n  if (spaces && !hits.length) {\n    const tree = await pod.fsTree().catch(() => null);\n    const files = JSON.stringify(tree ?? '');\n    if (rx.test(files)) hits.push('space-file');\n  }\n  report.check(\n    `${fixture}: its unique token \"${token}\" landed in REAL STATE (not prose)`,\n    hits.length > 0,\n    hits.length ? hits.join(', ') : 'NOT FOUND in any row or space file — the file was never read',\n  );\n  return hits;\n}\n\n// ── the app's OWN api routes — the layer the USER actually sees ─────────────────\n// A dashboard can render 0 / €0.00 on every tile while /app/data/<table> happily returns all its\n// rows, because the page's own aggregation route 500s. That really happened. Assert the routes the\n// PAGES fetch, not just the raw data API.\nasync function assertAppApi(report, pod, projectId, routes = []) {\n  for (const [route, check] of Object.entries(routes)) {\n    const res = await pod.appApi(projectId, route, undefined, 'GET').catch((e) => ({ status: 0, body: String(e) }));\n    const ok = res.status === 200 && (typeof check === 'function' ? check(res.body) : true);\n    report.check(`app's own route GET /${projectId}/api/${route} → 200 + real data`, ok, `status ${res.status}: ${JSON.stringify(res.body).slice(0, 160)}`);\n  }\n}\n\n// ── project-app assertion helper (build + read real rows) ────────────────────────\n// A real live-project app: compile it and confirm real assets came out, then read its DB rows.\n// (`built` lives at manifest.build.built and only reflects the LAST compile — so build explicitly\n//  and read the POST result, which carries assetManifest + routes — see the harness gotchas in the campaign prompt.)\nasync function assertLiveApp(report, pod, projectId, { minRowTables = {} } = {}) {\n  const build = await pod.appBuild(projectId).catch((e) => ({ built: false, error: String(e) }));\n  const assets = build?.assetManifest ?? [];\n  report.check('app compiles (built:true) with real JS assets', build?.built === true && assets.some((a) => /\\.js$/.test(a)), JSON.stringify({ built: build?.built, assets }).slice(0, 200));\n  report.check('app serves ≥1 page route', (build?.routes?.length ?? 0) >= 1, (build?.routes ?? []).map((x) => x.routePath).join(', '));\n  const page = await pod.appPage(projectId).catch((e) => ({ status: 0, body: String(e) }));\n  report.check(`/app/${projectId}/ serves 200 HTML`, page.status === 200 && String(page.body).includes('<!doctype'), `status ${page.status}, ${String(page.body).length} bytes`);\n  // minRowTables: { <table-regex>: <min rows> } — assert real data landed (moved into the db).\n  const manifest = await pod.appManifest(projectId).catch(() => ({}));\n  const names = (manifest?.tables ?? []).map((t) => (typeof t === 'string' ? t : t.name));\n  for (const [rx, min] of Object.entries(minRowTables)) {\n    const t = names.find((n) => new RegExp(rx, 'i').test(n));\n    const rows = t ? (await pod.appData(projectId, t).catch(() => ({ rows: [] }))).rows ?? [] : [];\n    report.check(`table /${rx}/ has ≥${min} rows`, rows.length >= min, `${t ?? '(none)'}: ${rows.length} rows`);\n  }\n  return build;\n}\n\n// ── main ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\nconst report = new Report(ID, TITLE);\nconst cp = loadCheckpoint();\nconst t0 = now();\n\nconst user = await getUser(LABEL);\nconsole.log(`user ${user.email} (${user.userId}) → ${user.pod}`);\n\nconst { changed } = await mergePodEnv(user.token, POD_ENV);\nif (changed) { await waitPodReady(user.token); await waitPodSettled(user.token); }\n\nconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\nconst projects = await pod.listProjects();\nif (PROJECT !== 'user' && !(projects.projects ?? []).some((p) => (p.id ?? p) === PROJECT)) {\n  await pod.createProject(PROJECT);\n}\ncp.projectId = PROJECT;\ncp.user = { label: LABEL, email: user.email, userId: user.userId };\n\nconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { projectId: PROJECT, onAsk: scriptedOnAsk(true), verbose: true });\nif (cp.sessionId && !FRESH) {\n  try { await thing.resume(cp.sessionId); } catch { cp.sessionId = await thing.start(); }\n} else {\n  cp.sessionId = await thing.start();\n}\nsaveCheckpoint(cp);\n\n// keep the pod warm so an idle scale-to-zero never kills the session mid-run\nconst keepalive = setInterval(() => {\n  pod.req('POST', '/api/keepalive', {}).catch(() => pod.req('POST', '/api/compute/wake', {}).catch(() => {}));\n}, 30_000);\nkeepalive.unref?.();\n\n// resilient send: survive a pod roll/restart (also exercises the auto-resume edge)\nconst _send = thing.send.bind(thing);\nthing.send = async (content, opts = {}) => {\n  for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n    try { return await _send(content, opts); }\n    catch (e) {\n      const msg = String(e?.body?.error ?? e?.message ?? '');\n      const lost = e?.status === 404 || /unknown session|404/.test(msg);\n      const errored = /entered error state/.test(msg);\n      if ((!lost && !errored) || attempt >= 3) throw e;\n      await waitPodReady(user.token).catch(() => {});\n      for (let i = 0; i < 40; i++) { if (await pod.listProjects().then(() => true).catch(() => false)) break; await sleep(4_000); }\n      if (lost && !errored) { try { await thing.resume(cp.sessionId); continue; } catch { /* fresh */ } }\n      cp.sessionId = await thing.start(); saveCheckpoint(cp);\n    }\n  }\n};\n\nconst metrics = { tokens: { in: 0, out: 0 } };\nconst acc = (turn) => { metrics.tokens.in += turn.tokens.in; metrics.tokens.out += turn.tokens.out; return turn; };\n\n// ═══ ACT I ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nif (ACTS.includes(1)) {\n  report.step('Act I — <name>', '<the contract this Act asserts>');\n  const t = acc(await thing.send('<the user message>', { timeoutMs: 900_000 }));\n  report.check('no eval/typecheck errors', t.errors.length === 0, JSON.stringify(t.errors).slice(0, 200));\n  // report.check('delegated to <space>', thing.didDelegate('<space>'), t.delegates.join(', '));\n  // ...assert on the trace + real side effects (files/rows/spaces), not the prose...\n  cp.acts.I = { passed: report.passed };\n  saveCheckpoint(cp);\n}\n\n// ═══ ACT II / III / IV — same shape; gate each on ACTS.includes(n) + checkpoint ═══\n// (Toggle scripted consent for a deny branch: thing.onAsk = scriptedOnAsk(false); ... reset to true.)\n//\n// ── Example: a file attachment → a live app with the data seeded in (the S06 pattern) ──\n// const attachment = await pod.upload(`${SDK_ORG}/scenarios/${ID}/fixtures/notes.md`);\n// report.check('file uploaded (kind=file)', attachment.kind === 'file', attachment.mediaType);\n// // Attachments ride the WS path (HTTP /message drops them). THING hands the file to a specialist\n// // via attachmentIds; the automator readDocument()s it and seeds rows via writeProjectTable(...,rows).\n// const t = acc(await thing.sendWithAttachments('<the user message>', [attachment], { timeoutMs: 1_500_000 }));\n// report.check('read the file (system-files)', thing.didDelegate('system-files'), t.delegates.join(', '));\n// await assertLiveApp(report, pod, PROJECT, { minRowTables: { 'flight|itinerary': 5, 'accommodation|hotel': 6 } });\n//\n// ── Example: a LATER update changes the db (use a NEW fact NOT already in any seed) ──\n// const before = JSON.stringify(await pod.appData(PROJECT, '<table>').catch(() => ({})));\n// acc(await thing.send('Mark X as done and record confirmation \"NEW-TOKEN-123\".', { timeoutMs: 900_000 }));\n// await sleep(4_000);\n// const after = JSON.stringify(await pod.appData(PROJECT, '<table>').catch(() => ({})));\n// report.check('the NEW fact landed in the db', !before.includes('new-token-123') && after.toLowerCase().includes('new-token-123'), 'before/after diff');\n//\n// ── Example: a signed inbound webhook fires a code-handler hook (0 LLM) ──\n// const res = await signedInbound(pod, 'demo', { message: { message_id: 1, text: 'TIP: hello', chat: { id: 'c1' }, from: { id: 'u1' } } }, POD_ENV.INTEGRATION_DEMO_WEBHOOK_SECRET);\n// report.check('inbound accepted (verify→emit)', res.status === 200 && res.body?.events >= 1, JSON.stringify(res.body));\n\n// ═══ verdict ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nconst stats = thing.stats();\nreport.step('Whole-session invariants', 'no eval/typecheck errors; routing not degraded over the run');\nreport.check('zero eval/typecheck errors across the session', stats.errors === 0, `${stats.errors} errors`);\nreport.metric('wall clock', ((now() - t0) / 60_000).toFixed(1), ' min');\nreport.metric('total tokens (in/out)', `${metrics.tokens.in} / ${metrics.tokens.out}`);\n\nreport.save(`${RESULTS}/report.md`);\nreport.saveTrace(`${RESULTS}/trace.json`, thing);\ncp.done = true; cp.summary = report.summary(); saveCheckpoint(cp);\nconsole.log(JSON.stringify(report.summary(), null, 2));\nprocess.exit(report.passed ? 0 : 1);\n","numLines":235,"startLine":1,"totalLines":235}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_CmMcLnCSY30Zd0MvlwXOUCEw","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/**\n2\t * THING session driver — talks to a real agent session over the pod's HTTP API and gives a\n3\t * scenario everything it needs to ASSERT on behaviour, not just on final text.\n4\t *\n5\t * Why HTTP and not the WebSocket the /chat SPA uses: the WS needs a dep and buys us nothing here.\n6\t * The pod exposes the same surface over HTTP (sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/web/agent-api.ts):\n7\t *\n8\t *   POST /api/sessions                      {projectId, agentSlug?, resumeSessionId?, budget?}\n9\t *   POST /api/sessions/:id/message          {content}                         → 202\n10\t *   GET  /api/sessions/:id/events?since=N&format=json                          → {events,lastSeq}\n11\t *   GET  /api/sessions/:id/asks?format=json                                    → {asks}\n12\t *   POST /api/sessions/:id/ask/:askId       {value}                            → answer a prompt\n13\t *\n14\t * The event stream is the full execution trace (sdk/org/libs/core/src/sandbox/trace.ts), so a\n15\t * scenario can assert on the things that actually matter — which agents THING delegated to, which\n16\t * consent-marked globals it called, which yields resolved, tokens burned, errors raised — instead\n17\t * of grading a paragraph of prose.\n18\t *\n19\t * IMPORTANT (consent): the consent prompter is only wired for INTERACTIVE sessions\n20\t * (session-manager.ts — `consentPrompter: args.interactive ? … : undefined`). A session created\n21\t * through `POST /api/sessions` is interactive, so consent cards appear as asks here. Headless\n22\t * paths (hooks, delegates, webhook dispatch) fail closed by design — that is a feature to assert,\n23\t * not a bug to work around.\n24\t */\n25\t\n26\tconst sleep = (ms) => new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, ms));\n27\t\n28\texport class ThingSession {\n29\t  /**\n30\t   * @param {import('./pod.mjs').Pod} pod\n31\t   * @param {object} opts\n32\t   * @param {string} [opts.projectId='user']   project to run in ('user' = the default project)\n33\t   * @param {string} [opts.agentSlug='thing']  THING is the default agent\n34\t   * @param {string} [opts.spaceRef]           bind to a project SPACE's agent (`<space>/<agent>`)\n35\t   *        instead of THING — the only way to exercise that specialist's OWN capability profile.\n36\t   * @param {(descriptor:object)=>unknown} [opts.onAsk]  answer asks (consent cards, forms).\n37\t   *        Return `undefined` to leave the ask open (the scenario answers it manually).\n38\t   * @param {boolean} [opts.verbose=false]     stream a live log to stdout\n39\t   */\n40\t  constructor(pod, opts = {}) {\n41\t    this.pod = pod;\n42\t    this.projectId = opts.projectId ?? 'user';\n43\t    this.agentSlug = opts.agentSlug ?? 'thing';\n44\t    this.spaceRef = opts.spaceRef;\n45\t    this.onAsk = opts.onAsk;\n46\t    this.verbose = opts.verbose ?? false;\n47\t    this.sessionId = null;\n48\t    /** every trace event seen, in order — the scenario's source of truth */\n49\t    this.events = [];\n50\t    /** asks the driver saw, with what it answered */\n51\t    this.asks = [];\n52\t    this.lastSeq = 0;\n53\t  }\n54\t\n55\t  log(...a) {\n56\t    if (this.verbose) console.log('[thing]', ...a);\n57\t  }\n58\t\n59\t  /** Create the session. Init is async pod-side — `send()` waits it out. */\n60\t  async start({ resumeSessionId, budget, spaceRef = this.spaceRef } = {}) {\n61\t    const body = {\n62\t      projectId: this.projectId,\n63\t      agentSlug: this.agentSlug,\n64\t      // Bind the session to a PROJECT SPACE's own agent (`<space>/<agent>`) instead of THING\n65\t      // (session-manager `_initProjectSession` → `parseSpaceRef`). This is what lets a scenario\n66\t      // probe one specialist's real capability profile directly, rather than inferring it from\n67\t      // what THING chose to delegate.\n68\t      ...(spaceRef ? { spaceRef } : {}),\n69\t      ...(resumeSessionId ? { resumeSessionId } : {}),\n70\t      ...(budget ? { budget } : {}),\n71\t    };\n72\t    const { sessionId } = await this.pod.req('POST', '/api/sessions', body);\n73\t    this.sessionId = sessionId;\n74\t    this.log('session', sessionId);\n75\t    return sessionId;\n76\t  }\n77\t\n78\t  /** Resume an existing session id (post-restart auto-resume scenario). */\n79\t  async resume(sessionId) {\n80\t    return this.start({ resumeSessionId: sessionId });\n81\t  }\n82\t\n83\t  /**\n84\t   * Fast-forward past a RESUMED session's existing trace without attributing it to the next turn.\n85\t   *\n86\t   * A scenario that runs Act-by-Act (`--acts=`) resumes the same session from a FRESH process, where\n87\t   * `lastSeq` starts at 0 — so the first `pullEvents()` replays the WHOLE session history and\n88\t   * `turn(startSeq)` folds it into the first turn's slice. Any assertion over that slice then reads\n89\t   * *earlier Acts'* displays: scenario 10 saw a restraint check \"pass\" on a build summary printed\n90\t   * two Acts ago. Call this right after `start()`/`resume()` so a turn's events are only its own.\n91\t   */\n92\t  async syncToTail() {\n93\t    for (let i = 0; i < 30; i++) {\n94\t      const before = this.lastSeq;\n95\t      await this.pullEvents();\n96\t      if (this.lastSeq === before) break;\n97\t      await sleep(200);\n98\t    }\n99\t    this.events.length = 0; // replayed history is not the next turn's work\n100\t    return this.lastSeq;\n101\t  }\n102\t\n103\t  /**\n104\t   * Pull new trace events since `lastSeq`.\n105\t   *\n106\t   * A long turn can spawn many delegate/headless sub-sessions; on a small pod (`maxSessions`) the\n107\t   * session manager may EVICT this top-level session shortly after its turn completes, so a poll\n108\t   * then 404s (\"unknown session\"). That is not a turn failure — the work already landed (assert it\n109\t   * on real pod state). So a 404 is surfaced as a soft signal (`this.sessionGone = true`) rather\n110\t   * than thrown; the settle loop treats it as turn-end once work has been seen.\n111\t   */\n112\t  async pullEvents() {\n113\t    let res;\n114\t    try {\n115\t      res = await this.pod.req('GET', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/events?since=${this.lastSeq}&format=json`);\n116\t    } catch (err) {\n117\t      if (err?.status === 404) {\n118\t        this.sessionGone = true;\n119\t        return [];\n120\t      }\n121\t      throw err;\n122\t    }\n123\t    const { events, lastSeq } = res;\n124\t    for (const e of events ?? []) {\n125\t      this.events.push(e.event);\n126\t      if (this.verbose) this.#logEvent(e.event);\n127\t    }\n128\t    if (typeof lastSeq === 'number') this.lastSeq = lastSeq;\n129\t    return events ?? [];\n130\t  }\n131\t\n132\t  #logEvent(ev) {\n133\t    switch (ev.type) {\n134\t      case 'yield':\n135\t        this.log(`  yield ${ev.kind}`, JSON.stringify(ev.args)?.slice(0, 140));\n136\t        break;\n137\t      case 'display':\n138\t        this.log('  display', JSON.stringify(ev.descriptor)?.slice(0, 200));\n139\t        break;\n140\t      case 'node_start':\n141\t        this.log(`  node_start ${ev.kind} ${ev.label}`);\n142\t        break;\n143\t      case 'node_end':\n144\t        this.log(`  node_end ${ev.nodeId} ${ev.status} ${ev.durationMs}ms`);\n145\t        break;\n146\t      case 'eval_error':\n147\t      case 'typecheck_error':\n148\t        this.log(`  !! ${ev.type}: ${ev.message?.slice(0, 200)}`);\n149\t        break;\n150\t      default:\n151\t        break;\n152\t    }\n153\t  }\n154\t\n155\t  /** Open asks, with the raw descriptor (a ConsentCard is `descriptor.type === 'ConsentCard'`). */\n156\t  async openAsks() {\n157\t    const { asks } = await this.pod.req('GET', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/asks?format=json`);\n158\t    return asks ?? [];\n159\t  }\n160\t\n161\t  /**\n162\t   * Answer an ask. Consent approval is anything in {true, 'approve', {approved:true},\n163\t   * {approve:true}} (core/src/globals/consent.ts `isConsentApproval`); ANYTHING else — including\n164\t   * null — is a denial.\n165\t   */\n166\t  async answerAsk(askId, value) {\n167\t    await this.pod.req('POST', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/ask/${askId}`, { value });\n168\t    this.log('answered ask', askId, JSON.stringify(value));\n169\t  }\n170\t\n171\t  /**\n172\t   * Send a user message and wait for the turn to settle.\n173\t   *\n174\t   * \"Settled\" = the session is idle AND the trace has stopped growing for `quietMs`. We can't\n175\t   * key on a single `turn_end` because delegates/forks emit their own in sub-contexts; the\n176\t   * idle+quiet pair is the only reliable edge over HTTP.\n177\t   *\n178\t   * While waiting we drain asks through `onAsk` — that is how consent cards get approved mid-turn.\n179\t   * A turn blocked on an unanswered ask never goes idle, so an un-handled consent card surfaces as\n180\t   * a timeout with the ask still open (which the scenario can assert on).\n181\t   */\n182\t  /**\n183\t   * Ensure `this.sessionId` still exists; if it was evicted (`maxSessions` on a small pod), start a\n184\t   * fresh session — resuming the old id when the pod still has its snapshot, else a clean new one.\n185\t   * The project (its spaces, app, db) persists on disk regardless, so a re-established session still\n186\t   * sees everything built so far; only in-VM conversation memory is lost (acceptable — the scenario\n187\t   * drives self-contained follow-ups).\n188\t   */\n189\t  async #ensureAlive() {\n190\t    if (!this.sessionId) return;\n191\t    const list = await this.pod.req('GET', '/api/sessions').catch(() => ({ sessions: [] }));\n192\t    const alive = (list.sessions ?? []).some((s) => s.sessionId === this.sessionId);\n193\t    if (alive) return;\n194\t    this.log('session evicted — re-establishing');\n195\t    const prev = this.sessionId;\n196\t    try {\n197\t      await this.start({ resumeSessionId: prev });\n198\t    } catch {\n199\t      await this.start();\n200\t    }\n201\t    // The re-established session replays its whole persisted trace from seq 0. We ALREADY hold those\n202\t    // events, so appending the replay duplicates every past turn — and, worse, `turn(startSeq)` then\n203\t    // slices a window full of REPLAYED history and asserts on it as if it were the turn we just sent\n204\t    // (scenario 10 read a re-analysis of turn 1's images as the work of its \"yes\" turn). Drain the\n205\t    // replay to re-sync `lastSeq`, then discard it: it is history we already have.\n206\t    const held = this.events.length;\n207\t    this.lastSeq = 0;\n208\t    for (let i = 0; i < 30; i++) {\n209\t      const before = this.lastSeq;\n210\t      await this.pullEvents();\n211\t      if (this.lastSeq === before) break;\n212\t      await sleep(200);\n213\t    }\n214\t    this.events.length = held;\n215\t    this.sessionGone = false;\n216\t  }\n217\t\n218\t  async send(content, opts = {}) {\n219\t    await this.#ensureAlive();\n220\t    return this.#dispatchAndWait(\n221\t      () => this.pod.req('POST', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/message`, { content }),\n222\t      content,\n223\t      opts,\n224\t    );\n225\t  }\n226\t\n227\t  /**\n228\t   * Send a user message WITH attachments (the file-upload path the real UI uses).\n229\t   *\n230\t   * The HTTP `POST /message` route is content-only — it silently drops attachments\n231\t   * (`sessions.ts` wires `sendMessage: (content) => manager.sendMessage(id, content)`, no third\n232\t   * arg). Only the WebSocket path carries `attachmentIds` (`ws/agent.ts` →\n233\t   * `msg.attachments.map(a => a.id)`). So to attach a file we open the same `/api/ws` socket the\n234\t   * `/chat` SPA uses, send one `{type:'sendMessage', content, attachments}` frame, then fall back to\n235\t   * the normal HTTP trace-poll to await the turn (the socket also streams the trace, but reusing the\n236\t   * HTTP settle-loop keeps one code path for \"turn finished\").\n237\t   *\n238\t   * @param {string} content\n239\t   * @param {Array<{id:string,kind:string,mediaType:string,url?:string,filename?:string}>} attachments\n240\t   *        AttachmentRefs from `pod.upload()`. The server trusts only `id` (re-reads bytes by id).\n241\t   */\n242\t  async sendWithAttachments(content, attachments, opts = {}) {\n243\t    const refs = attachments.map((a) => ({\n244\t      id: a.id,\n245\t      kind: a.kind,\n246\t      mediaType: a.mediaType,\n247\t      url: a.url ?? `/api/uploads/${a.id}`,\n248\t      ...(a.filename ? { filename: a.filename } : {}),\n249\t    }));\n250\t    await this.#ensureAlive();\n251\t    return this.#dispatchAndWait(\n252\t      () => this.#wsSend({ type: 'sendMessage', content, attachments: refs }),\n253\t      `${content}  [+${refs.length} attachment(s)]`,\n254\t      opts,\n255\t    );\n256\t  }\n257\t\n258\t  /** Open the pod's chat WebSocket, send one frame, resolve when it's flushed, then close. */\n259\t  #wsSend(frame) {\n260\t    const wsBase = this.pod.base.replace(/^http/, 'ws');\n261\t    const tokenQ = this.pod.token ? `&access_token=${encodeURIComponent(this.pod.token)}` : '';\n262\t    const url = `${wsBase}/api/ws?sessionId=${this.sessionId}${tokenQ}`;\n263\t    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n264\t      const ws = new WebSocket(url); // Node ≥22 global WebSocket — zero-dep\n265\t      const fail = (e) => reject(e instanceof Error ? e : new Error(`ws error: ${JSON.stringify(e)}`));\n266\t      ws.addEventListener('open', () => {\n267\t        ws.send(JSON.stringify(frame));\n268\t        // Give the frame a beat to flush, then close; the turn is awaited over HTTP.\n269\t        setTimeout(() => {\n270\t          try {\n271\t            ws.close();\n272\t          } catch {\n273\t            /* ignore */\n274\t          }\n275\t          resolve();\n276\t        }, 750);\n277\t      });\n278\t      ws.addEventListener('error', fail);\n279\t    });\n280\t  }\n281\t\n282\t  async #dispatchAndWait(dispatch, logLine, { timeoutMs = 600_000, quietMs = 4_000, pollMs = 1_500 } = {}) {\n283\t    const startSeq = this.events.length;\n284\t    const t0 = Date.now();\n285\t    await dispatch();\n286\t    this.log('→', logLine.slice(0, 140));\n287\t\n288\t    let lastChange = Date.now();\n289\t    let sawWork = false;\n290\t    let quietSince = null;\n291\t    this.sessionGone = false;\n292\t\n293\t    while (Date.now() - t0 < timeoutMs) {\n294\t      const fresh = await this.pullEvents();\n295\t      if (fresh.length) {\n296\t        lastChange = Date.now();\n297\t        sawWork = true;\n298\t        quietSince = null;\n299\t      }\n300\t\n301\t      // The session vanished mid-turn (evicted past `maxSessions`, or the pod rolled/woke from\n302\t      // scale-to-zero under us — sessions are in-memory). We saw work, but we do NOT know the turn\n303\t      // FINISHED: a long build (build_specialist → deep_research → architect) can be cut off with\n304\t      // nothing durable written. Returning silently here reports a killed turn as a completed one —\n305\t      // that is how scenario 07's Act V \"built\" two sections and produced no space, table or page.\n306\t      // So flag it: `turn.interrupted` lets the caller re-send once the pod is back (see run.mjs).\n307\t      if (this.sessionGone) {\n308\t        if (sawWork) return { ...this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0), interrupted: true };\n309\t        throw new Error(`session ${this.sessionId} disappeared before doing any work (pod restart mid-init?)`);\n310\t      }\n311\t\n312\t      // Drain asks (consent cards, forms) — an unanswered ask stalls the turn forever.\n313\t      for (const ask of await this.openAsks().catch(() => [])) {\n314\t        if (this.asks.some((a) => a.id === ask.id)) continue;\n315\t        const answer = this.onAsk ? this.onAsk(ask.descriptor, ask) : undefined;\n316\t        this.asks.push({ id: ask.id, descriptor: ask.descriptor, answered: answer });\n317\t        if (answer !== undefined) {\n318\t          await this.answerAsk(ask.id, answer).catch(() => {});\n319\t          lastChange = Date.now();\n320\t        }\n321\t      }\n322\t\n323\t      const sessions = await this.pod.req('GET', '/api/sessions').catch(() => ({ sessions: [] }));\n324\t      const me = (sessions.sessions ?? []).find((s) => s.sessionId === this.sessionId);\n325\t      const idle = me?.status === 'idle';\n326\t      if (me?.status === 'error') {\n327\t        await this.pullEvents();\n328\t        throw new Error(`session entered error state: ${JSON.stringify(me)}`);\n329\t      }\n330\t      // The session is no longer LISTED, though we saw work. Same hazard as `sessionGone` above and\n331\t      // it must be flagged the same way: \"not resident any more\" does NOT mean \"the turn finished\".\n332\t      // A shared local server that a sibling lane restarts (or any drop of the in-memory session)\n333\t      // vanishes the entry mid-flight, and a turn that had only just dispatched its delegates gets\n334\t      // reported as a COMPLETED turn with no results. Scenario 10 then sent the user's \"yes\" into a\n335\t      // session that had never made the offer it was agreeing to, and every downstream Act failed on\n336\t      // a build that never happened. Flag it — `turn.interrupted` is the caller's cue to re-send.\n337\t      if (sawWork && !me && this.events.length > startSeq) {\n338\t        return { ...this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0), interrupted: true };\n339\t      }\n340\t\n341\t      if (sawWork && idle && Date.now() - lastChange >= quietMs) {\n342\t        if (quietSince === null) quietSince = Date.now();\n343\t        await this.pullEvents(); // final drain\n344\t        return this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0);\n345\t      }\n346\t      await sleep(pollMs);\n347\t    }\n348\t    await this.pullEvents();\n349\t    const open = await this.openAsks();\n350\t    throw Object.assign(\n351\t      new Error(\n352\t        `turn timed out after ${timeoutMs}ms` +\n353\t          (open.length ? ` with ${open.length} unanswered ask(s): ${JSON.stringify(open)}` : ''),\n354\t      ),\n355\t      { turn: this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0), openAsks: open },\n356\t    );\n357\t  }\n358\t\n359\t  /** A view over just the events of one turn, with the derived facts a scenario asserts on. */\n360\t  turn(startSeq = 0, durationMs = 0) {\n361\t    const evs = this.events.slice(startSeq);\n362\t    return {\n363\t      durationMs,\n364\t      events: evs,\n365\t      text: textOf(evs),\n366\t      /** ONLY the turn's final display — the reply the user actually reads. `text` concatenates every\n367\t       *  display in the slice, which on a RESUMED session can still include replayed history, so a\n368\t       *  check about \"what it answered\" must read this, never `text`. */\n369\t      lastText: lastTextOf(evs),\n370\t      yields: evs.filter((e) => e.type === 'yield').map((e) => ({ kind: e.kind, args: e.args })),\n371\t      delegates: evs\n372\t        .filter((e) => e.type === 'yield' && e.kind === 'delegate')\n373\t        .map((e) => delegateRef(e.args)),\n374\t      // `attempt` is load-bearing: the turn loop retries a typecheck/eval error up to `maxRetries`\n375\t      // (default 3); an error logged at attempt < 3 is RECOVERED (the loop kept going and reset the\n376\t      // counter on the next success), one at attempt >= 3 made the loop give up (`return 'error'`).\n377\t      // A scenario that must distinguish \"recovered = metric\" from \"unrecovered = hard fail\" (per the\n378\t      // campaign's error policy) needs this — dropping it made every recovered slip look fatal.\n379\t      errors: evs\n380\t        .filter((e) => e.type === 'eval_error' || e.type === 'typecheck_error')\n381\t        .map((e) => ({ type: e.type, message: e.message, statement: e.statement, attempt: e.attempt })),\n382\t      tokens: evs.reduce(\n383\t        (acc, e) =>\n384\t          e.type === 'llm_response'\n385\t            ? { in: acc.in + (e.inputTokens ?? 0), out: acc.out + (e.outputTokens ?? 0) }\n386\t            : acc,\n387\t        { in: 0, out: 0 },\n388\t      ),\n389\t      llmCalls: evs.filter((e) => e.type === 'llm_response').length,\n390\t      nodes: evs\n391\t        .filter((e) => e.type === 'node_end')\n392\t        .map((e) => ({ id: e.nodeId, status: e.status, ms: e.durationMs, error: e.error })),\n393\t    };\n394\t  }\n395\t\n396\t  /** Did the agent call this yield kind anywhere in the session? (e.g. 'installSpace') */\n397\t  didYield = (kind) => this.events.some((e) => e.type === 'yield' && e.kind === kind);\n398\t  /** Did it delegate to this `space/agent` (or just this space)? */\n399\t  didDelegate = (ref) =>\n400\t    this.events.some(\n401\t      (e) => e.type === 'yield' && e.kind === 'delegate' && delegateRef(e.args).startsWith(ref),\n402\t    );\n403\t  /** All consent cards raised this session. */\n404\t  consentCards = () => this.asks.filter((a) => a.descriptor?.type === 'ConsentCard');\n405\t\n406\t  /** The default `maxRetries` in the turn loop (core/src/eval/turn-loop.ts). An error logged at an\n407\t   *  attempt >= this made the loop give up — it was NOT recovered. */\n408\t  static MAX_RETRIES = 3;\n409\t  /** Errors the turn loop could NOT recover from (attempt reached maxRetries). Recovered slips\n410\t   *  (attempt < maxRetries) are a metric, not a failure — see the campaign error policy. */\n411\t  unrecoveredErrors = () =>\n412\t    this.turn(0, 0).errors.filter((e) => (e.attempt ?? 1) >= ThingSession.MAX_RETRIES);\n413\t\n414\t  /** Full session totals — for the performance table in the scenario report. */\n415\t  stats() {\n416\t    const t = this.turn(0, 0);\n417\t    return {\n418\t      events: this.events.length,\n419\t      llmCalls: t.llmCalls,\n420\t      tokens: t.tokens,\n421\t      errors: t.errors.length,\n422\t      unrecoveredErrors: this.unrecoveredErrors().length,\n423\t      delegates: t.delegates,\n424\t      yieldKinds: [...new Set(t.yields.map((y) => y.kind))],\n425\t    };\n426\t  }\n427\t}\n428\t\n429\t/** Human-readable delegate target from the yield args (`{space, agent, action}` or positional). */\n430\tfunction delegateRef(args) {\n431\t  if (Array.isArray(args)) return args.slice(0, 3).filter(Boolean).join('/');\n432\t  if (args && typeof args === 'object') {\n433\t    const { space, agent, action } = args;\n434\t    return [space, agent, action].filter(Boolean).join('/');\n435\t  }\n436\t  return String(args);\n437\t}\n438\t\n439\t/** The prose THING showed the user: display() descriptors + the final assistant text. */\n440\texport function textOf(events) {\n441\t  const out = [];\n442\t  for (const e of events) {\n443\t    if (e.type === 'display') {\n444\t      const d = e.descriptor;\n445\t      const s =\n446\t        typeof d === 'string'\n447\t          ? d\n448\t          : (d?.props?.text ?? d?.props?.children ?? d?.props?.content ?? JSON.stringify(d));\n449\t      out.push(typeof s === 'string' ? s : JSON.stringify(s));\n450\t    }\n451\t  }\n452\t  return out.join('\\n');\n453\t}\n454\t\n455\t/** The LAST thing THING displayed — its final reply for this turn (see `turn().lastText`). */\n456\texport function lastTextOf(events) {\n457\t  for (let i = events.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n458\t    const e = events[i];\n459\t    if (e.type !== 'display') continue;\n460\t    const d = e.descriptor;\n461\t    const s =\n462\t      typeof d === 'string'\n463\t        ? d\n464\t        : (d?.props?.text ?? d?.props?.children ?? d?.props?.content ?? JSON.stringify(d));\n465\t    const out = typeof s === 'string' ? s : JSON.stringify(s);\n466\t    if (out && out.trim()) return out;\n467\t  }\n468\t  return '';\n469\t}\n470\t\n471\t/** Approve every consent card; leave other asks for the scenario. */\n472\texport const approveAllConsent = (descriptor) =>\n473\t  descriptor?.type === 'ConsentCard' ? true : undefined;\n474\t/** Deny every consent card (for the denial branch of the consent scenario). */\n475\texport const denyAllConsent = (descriptor) =>\n476\t  descriptor?.type === 'ConsentCard' ? false : undefined;\n477\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f21d2fda-94ab-442d-8f32-017580283d3b","uuid":"4bfb93e5-59b0-478f-8dd0-90db5eb61d1a","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:53:17.042Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/lib/thing.mjs","content":"/**\n * THING session driver — talks to a real agent session over the pod's HTTP API and gives a\n * scenario everything it needs to ASSERT on behaviour, not just on final text.\n *\n * Why HTTP and not the WebSocket the /chat SPA uses: the WS needs a dep and buys us nothing here.\n * The pod exposes the same surface over HTTP (sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/web/agent-api.ts):\n *\n *   POST /api/sessions                      {projectId, agentSlug?, resumeSessionId?, budget?}\n *   POST /api/sessions/:id/message          {content}                         → 202\n *   GET  /api/sessions/:id/events?since=N&format=json                          → {events,lastSeq}\n *   GET  /api/sessions/:id/asks?format=json                                    → {asks}\n *   POST /api/sessions/:id/ask/:askId       {value}                            → answer a prompt\n *\n * The event stream is the full execution trace (sdk/org/libs/core/src/sandbox/trace.ts), so a\n * scenario can assert on the things that actually matter — which agents THING delegated to, which\n * consent-marked globals it called, which yields resolved, tokens burned, errors raised — instead\n * of grading a paragraph of prose.\n *\n * IMPORTANT (consent): the consent prompter is only wired for INTERACTIVE sessions\n * (session-manager.ts — `consentPrompter: args.interactive ? … : undefined`). A session created\n * through `POST /api/sessions` is interactive, so consent cards appear as asks here. Headless\n * paths (hooks, delegates, webhook dispatch) fail closed by design — that is a feature to assert,\n * not a bug to work around.\n */\n\nconst sleep = (ms) => new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, ms));\n\nexport class ThingSession {\n  /**\n   * @param {import('./pod.mjs').Pod} pod\n   * @param {object} opts\n   * @param {string} [opts.projectId='user']   project to run in ('user' = the default project)\n   * @param {string} [opts.agentSlug='thing']  THING is the default agent\n   * @param {string} [opts.spaceRef]           bind to a project SPACE's agent (`<space>/<agent>`)\n   *        instead of THING — the only way to exercise that specialist's OWN capability profile.\n   * @param {(descriptor:object)=>unknown} [opts.onAsk]  answer asks (consent cards, forms).\n   *        Return `undefined` to leave the ask open (the scenario answers it manually).\n   * @param {boolean} [opts.verbose=false]     stream a live log to stdout\n   */\n  constructor(pod, opts = {}) {\n    this.pod = pod;\n    this.projectId = opts.projectId ?? 'user';\n    this.agentSlug = opts.agentSlug ?? 'thing';\n    this.spaceRef = opts.spaceRef;\n    this.onAsk = opts.onAsk;\n    this.verbose = opts.verbose ?? false;\n    this.sessionId = null;\n    /** every trace event seen, in order — the scenario's source of truth */\n    this.events = [];\n    /** asks the driver saw, with what it answered */\n    this.asks = [];\n    this.lastSeq = 0;\n  }\n\n  log(...a) {\n    if (this.verbose) console.log('[thing]', ...a);\n  }\n\n  /** Create the session. Init is async pod-side — `send()` waits it out. */\n  async start({ resumeSessionId, budget, spaceRef = this.spaceRef } = {}) {\n    const body = {\n      projectId: this.projectId,\n      agentSlug: this.agentSlug,\n      // Bind the session to a PROJECT SPACE's own agent (`<space>/<agent>`) instead of THING\n      // (session-manager `_initProjectSession` → `parseSpaceRef`). This is what lets a scenario\n      // probe one specialist's real capability profile directly, rather than inferring it from\n      // what THING chose to delegate.\n      ...(spaceRef ? { spaceRef } : {}),\n      ...(resumeSessionId ? { resumeSessionId } : {}),\n      ...(budget ? { budget } : {}),\n    };\n    const { sessionId } = await this.pod.req('POST', '/api/sessions', body);\n    this.sessionId = sessionId;\n    this.log('session', sessionId);\n    return sessionId;\n  }\n\n  /** Resume an existing session id (post-restart auto-resume scenario). */\n  async resume(sessionId) {\n    return this.start({ resumeSessionId: sessionId });\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Fast-forward past a RESUMED session's existing trace without attributing it to the next turn.\n   *\n   * A scenario that runs Act-by-Act (`--acts=`) resumes the same session from a FRESH process, where\n   * `lastSeq` starts at 0 — so the first `pullEvents()` replays the WHOLE session history and\n   * `turn(startSeq)` folds it into the first turn's slice. Any assertion over that slice then reads\n   * *earlier Acts'* displays: scenario 10 saw a restraint check \"pass\" on a build summary printed\n   * two Acts ago. Call this right after `start()`/`resume()` so a turn's events are only its own.\n   */\n  async syncToTail() {\n    for (let i = 0; i < 30; i++) {\n      const before = this.lastSeq;\n      await this.pullEvents();\n      if (this.lastSeq === before) break;\n      await sleep(200);\n    }\n    this.events.length = 0; // replayed history is not the next turn's work\n    return this.lastSeq;\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Pull new trace events since `lastSeq`.\n   *\n   * A long turn can spawn many delegate/headless sub-sessions; on a small pod (`maxSessions`) the\n   * session manager may EVICT this top-level session shortly after its turn completes, so a poll\n   * then 404s (\"unknown session\"). That is not a turn failure — the work already landed (assert it\n   * on real pod state). So a 404 is surfaced as a soft signal (`this.sessionGone = true`) rather\n   * than thrown; the settle loop treats it as turn-end once work has been seen.\n   */\n  async pullEvents() {\n    let res;\n    try {\n      res = await this.pod.req('GET', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/events?since=${this.lastSeq}&format=json`);\n    } catch (err) {\n      if (err?.status === 404) {\n        this.sessionGone = true;\n        return [];\n      }\n      throw err;\n    }\n    const { events, lastSeq } = res;\n    for (const e of events ?? []) {\n      this.events.push(e.event);\n      if (this.verbose) this.#logEvent(e.event);\n    }\n    if (typeof lastSeq === 'number') this.lastSeq = lastSeq;\n    return events ?? [];\n  }\n\n  #logEvent(ev) {\n    switch (ev.type) {\n      case 'yield':\n        this.log(`  yield ${ev.kind}`, JSON.stringify(ev.args)?.slice(0, 140));\n        break;\n      case 'display':\n        this.log('  display', JSON.stringify(ev.descriptor)?.slice(0, 200));\n        break;\n      case 'node_start':\n        this.log(`  node_start ${ev.kind} ${ev.label}`);\n        break;\n      case 'node_end':\n        this.log(`  node_end ${ev.nodeId} ${ev.status} ${ev.durationMs}ms`);\n        break;\n      case 'eval_error':\n      case 'typecheck_error':\n        this.log(`  !! ${ev.type}: ${ev.message?.slice(0, 200)}`);\n        break;\n      default:\n        break;\n    }\n  }\n\n  /** Open asks, with the raw descriptor (a ConsentCard is `descriptor.type === 'ConsentCard'`). */\n  async openAsks() {\n    const { asks } = await this.pod.req('GET', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/asks?format=json`);\n    return asks ?? [];\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Answer an ask. Consent approval is anything in {true, 'approve', {approved:true},\n   * {approve:true}} (core/src/globals/consent.ts `isConsentApproval`); ANYTHING else — including\n   * null — is a denial.\n   */\n  async answerAsk(askId, value) {\n    await this.pod.req('POST', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/ask/${askId}`, { value });\n    this.log('answered ask', askId, JSON.stringify(value));\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Send a user message and wait for the turn to settle.\n   *\n   * \"Settled\" = the session is idle AND the trace has stopped growing for `quietMs`. We can't\n   * key on a single `turn_end` because delegates/forks emit their own in sub-contexts; the\n   * idle+quiet pair is the only reliable edge over HTTP.\n   *\n   * While waiting we drain asks through `onAsk` — that is how consent cards get approved mid-turn.\n   * A turn blocked on an unanswered ask never goes idle, so an un-handled consent card surfaces as\n   * a timeout with the ask still open (which the scenario can assert on).\n   */\n  /**\n   * Ensure `this.sessionId` still exists; if it was evicted (`maxSessions` on a small pod), start a\n   * fresh session — resuming the old id when the pod still has its snapshot, else a clean new one.\n   * The project (its spaces, app, db) persists on disk regardless, so a re-established session still\n   * sees everything built so far; only in-VM conversation memory is lost (acceptable — the scenario\n   * drives self-contained follow-ups).\n   */\n  async #ensureAlive() {\n    if (!this.sessionId) return;\n    const list = await this.pod.req('GET', '/api/sessions').catch(() => ({ sessions: [] }));\n    const alive = (list.sessions ?? []).some((s) => s.sessionId === this.sessionId);\n    if (alive) return;\n    this.log('session evicted — re-establishing');\n    const prev = this.sessionId;\n    try {\n      await this.start({ resumeSessionId: prev });\n    } catch {\n      await this.start();\n    }\n    // The re-established session replays its whole persisted trace from seq 0. We ALREADY hold those\n    // events, so appending the replay duplicates every past turn — and, worse, `turn(startSeq)` then\n    // slices a window full of REPLAYED history and asserts on it as if it were the turn we just sent\n    // (scenario 10 read a re-analysis of turn 1's images as the work of its \"yes\" turn). Drain the\n    // replay to re-sync `lastSeq`, then discard it: it is history we already have.\n    const held = this.events.length;\n    this.lastSeq = 0;\n    for (let i = 0; i < 30; i++) {\n      const before = this.lastSeq;\n      await this.pullEvents();\n      if (this.lastSeq === before) break;\n      await sleep(200);\n    }\n    this.events.length = held;\n    this.sessionGone = false;\n  }\n\n  async send(content, opts = {}) {\n    await this.#ensureAlive();\n    return this.#dispatchAndWait(\n      () => this.pod.req('POST', `/api/sessions/${this.sessionId}/message`, { content }),\n      content,\n      opts,\n    );\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Send a user message WITH attachments (the file-upload path the real UI uses).\n   *\n   * The HTTP `POST /message` route is content-only — it silently drops attachments\n   * (`sessions.ts` wires `sendMessage: (content) => manager.sendMessage(id, content)`, no third\n   * arg). Only the WebSocket path carries `attachmentIds` (`ws/agent.ts` →\n   * `msg.attachments.map(a => a.id)`). So to attach a file we open the same `/api/ws` socket the\n   * `/chat` SPA uses, send one `{type:'sendMessage', content, attachments}` frame, then fall back to\n   * the normal HTTP trace-poll to await the turn (the socket also streams the trace, but reusing the\n   * HTTP settle-loop keeps one code path for \"turn finished\").\n   *\n   * @param {string} content\n   * @param {Array<{id:string,kind:string,mediaType:string,url?:string,filename?:string}>} attachments\n   *        AttachmentRefs from `pod.upload()`. The server trusts only `id` (re-reads bytes by id).\n   */\n  async sendWithAttachments(content, attachments, opts = {}) {\n    const refs = attachments.map((a) => ({\n      id: a.id,\n      kind: a.kind,\n      mediaType: a.mediaType,\n      url: a.url ?? `/api/uploads/${a.id}`,\n      ...(a.filename ? { filename: a.filename } : {}),\n    }));\n    await this.#ensureAlive();\n    return this.#dispatchAndWait(\n      () => this.#wsSend({ type: 'sendMessage', content, attachments: refs }),\n      `${content}  [+${refs.length} attachment(s)]`,\n      opts,\n    );\n  }\n\n  /** Open the pod's chat WebSocket, send one frame, resolve when it's flushed, then close. */\n  #wsSend(frame) {\n    const wsBase = this.pod.base.replace(/^http/, 'ws');\n    const tokenQ = this.pod.token ? `&access_token=${encodeURIComponent(this.pod.token)}` : '';\n    const url = `${wsBase}/api/ws?sessionId=${this.sessionId}${tokenQ}`;\n    return new Promise((resolve, reject) => {\n      const ws = new WebSocket(url); // Node ≥22 global WebSocket — zero-dep\n      const fail = (e) => reject(e instanceof Error ? e : new Error(`ws error: ${JSON.stringify(e)}`));\n      ws.addEventListener('open', () => {\n        ws.send(JSON.stringify(frame));\n        // Give the frame a beat to flush, then close; the turn is awaited over HTTP.\n        setTimeout(() => {\n          try {\n            ws.close();\n          } catch {\n            /* ignore */\n          }\n          resolve();\n        }, 750);\n      });\n      ws.addEventListener('error', fail);\n    });\n  }\n\n  async #dispatchAndWait(dispatch, logLine, { timeoutMs = 600_000, quietMs = 4_000, pollMs = 1_500 } = {}) {\n    const startSeq = this.events.length;\n    const t0 = Date.now();\n    await dispatch();\n    this.log('→', logLine.slice(0, 140));\n\n    let lastChange = Date.now();\n    let sawWork = false;\n    let quietSince = null;\n    this.sessionGone = false;\n\n    while (Date.now() - t0 < timeoutMs) {\n      const fresh = await this.pullEvents();\n      if (fresh.length) {\n        lastChange = Date.now();\n        sawWork = true;\n        quietSince = null;\n      }\n\n      // The session vanished mid-turn (evicted past `maxSessions`, or the pod rolled/woke from\n      // scale-to-zero under us — sessions are in-memory). We saw work, but we do NOT know the turn\n      // FINISHED: a long build (build_specialist → deep_research → architect) can be cut off with\n      // nothing durable written. Returning silently here reports a killed turn as a completed one —\n      // that is how scenario 07's Act V \"built\" two sections and produced no space, table or page.\n      // So flag it: `turn.interrupted` lets the caller re-send once the pod is back (see run.mjs).\n      if (this.sessionGone) {\n        if (sawWork) return { ...this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0), interrupted: true };\n        throw new Error(`session ${this.sessionId} disappeared before doing any work (pod restart mid-init?)`);\n      }\n\n      // Drain asks (consent cards, forms) — an unanswered ask stalls the turn forever.\n      for (const ask of await this.openAsks().catch(() => [])) {\n        if (this.asks.some((a) => a.id === ask.id)) continue;\n        const answer = this.onAsk ? this.onAsk(ask.descriptor, ask) : undefined;\n        this.asks.push({ id: ask.id, descriptor: ask.descriptor, answered: answer });\n        if (answer !== undefined) {\n          await this.answerAsk(ask.id, answer).catch(() => {});\n          lastChange = Date.now();\n        }\n      }\n\n      const sessions = await this.pod.req('GET', '/api/sessions').catch(() => ({ sessions: [] }));\n      const me = (sessions.sessions ?? []).find((s) => s.sessionId === this.sessionId);\n      const idle = me?.status === 'idle';\n      if (me?.status === 'error') {\n        await this.pullEvents();\n        throw new Error(`session entered error state: ${JSON.stringify(me)}`);\n      }\n      // The session is no longer LISTED, though we saw work. Same hazard as `sessionGone` above and\n      // it must be flagged the same way: \"not resident any more\" does NOT mean \"the turn finished\".\n      // A shared local server that a sibling lane restarts (or any drop of the in-memory session)\n      // vanishes the entry mid-flight, and a turn that had only just dispatched its delegates gets\n      // reported as a COMPLETED turn with no results. Scenario 10 then sent the user's \"yes\" into a\n      // session that had never made the offer it was agreeing to, and every downstream Act failed on\n      // a build that never happened. Flag it — `turn.interrupted` is the caller's cue to re-send.\n      if (sawWork && !me && this.events.length > startSeq) {\n        return { ...this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0), interrupted: true };\n      }\n\n      if (sawWork && idle && Date.now() - lastChange >= quietMs) {\n        if (quietSince === null) quietSince = Date.now();\n        await this.pullEvents(); // final drain\n        return this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0);\n      }\n      await sleep(pollMs);\n    }\n    await this.pullEvents();\n    const open = await this.openAsks();\n    throw Object.assign(\n      new Error(\n        `turn timed out after ${timeoutMs}ms` +\n          (open.length ? ` with ${open.length} unanswered ask(s): ${JSON.stringify(open)}` : ''),\n      ),\n      { turn: this.turn(startSeq, Date.now() - t0), openAsks: open },\n    );\n  }\n\n  /** A view over just the events of one turn, with the derived facts a scenario asserts on. */\n  turn(startSeq = 0, durationMs = 0) {\n    const evs = this.events.slice(startSeq);\n    return {\n      durationMs,\n      events: evs,\n      text: textOf(evs),\n      /** ONLY the turn's final display — the reply the user actually reads. `text` concatenates every\n       *  display in the slice, which on a RESUMED session can still include replayed history, so a\n       *  check about \"what it answered\" must read this, never `text`. */\n      lastText: lastTextOf(evs),\n      yields: evs.filter((e) => e.type === 'yield').map((e) => ({ kind: e.kind, args: e.args })),\n      delegates: evs\n        .filter((e) => e.type === 'yield' && e.kind === 'delegate')\n        .map((e) => delegateRef(e.args)),\n      // `attempt` is load-bearing: the turn loop retries a typecheck/eval error up to `maxRetries`\n      // (default 3); an error logged at attempt < 3 is RECOVERED (the loop kept going and reset the\n      // counter on the next success), one at attempt >= 3 made the loop give up (`return 'error'`).\n      // A scenario that must distinguish \"recovered = metric\" from \"unrecovered = hard fail\" (per the\n      // campaign's error policy) needs this — dropping it made every recovered slip look fatal.\n      errors: evs\n        .filter((e) => e.type === 'eval_error' || e.type === 'typecheck_error')\n        .map((e) => ({ type: e.type, message: e.message, statement: e.statement, attempt: e.attempt })),\n      tokens: evs.reduce(\n        (acc, e) =>\n          e.type === 'llm_response'\n            ? { in: acc.in + (e.inputTokens ?? 0), out: acc.out + (e.outputTokens ?? 0) }\n            : acc,\n        { in: 0, out: 0 },\n      ),\n      llmCalls: evs.filter((e) => e.type === 'llm_response').length,\n      nodes: evs\n        .filter((e) => e.type === 'node_end')\n        .map((e) => ({ id: e.nodeId, status: e.status, ms: e.durationMs, error: e.error })),\n    };\n  }\n\n  /** Did the agent call this yield kind anywhere in the session? (e.g. 'installSpace') */\n  didYield = (kind) => this.events.some((e) => e.type === 'yield' && e.kind === kind);\n  /** Did it delegate to this `space/agent` (or just this space)? */\n  didDelegate = (ref) =>\n    this.events.some(\n      (e) => e.type === 'yield' && e.kind === 'delegate' && delegateRef(e.args).startsWith(ref),\n    );\n  /** All consent cards raised this session. */\n  consentCards = () => this.asks.filter((a) => a.descriptor?.type === 'ConsentCard');\n\n  /** The default `maxRetries` in the turn loop (core/src/eval/turn-loop.ts). An error logged at an\n   *  attempt >= this made the loop give up — it was NOT recovered. */\n  static MAX_RETRIES = 3;\n  /** Errors the turn loop could NOT recover from (attempt reached maxRetries). Recovered slips\n   *  (attempt < maxRetries) are a metric, not a failure — see the campaign error policy. */\n  unrecoveredErrors = () =>\n    this.turn(0, 0).errors.filter((e) => (e.attempt ?? 1) >= ThingSession.MAX_RETRIES);\n\n  /** Full session totals — for the performance table in the scenario report. */\n  stats() {\n    const t = this.turn(0, 0);\n    return {\n      events: this.events.length,\n      llmCalls: t.llmCalls,\n      tokens: t.tokens,\n      errors: t.errors.length,\n      unrecoveredErrors: this.unrecoveredErrors().length,\n      delegates: t.delegates,\n      yieldKinds: [...new Set(t.yields.map((y) => y.kind))],\n    };\n  }\n}\n\n/** Human-readable delegate target from the yield args (`{space, agent, action}` or positional). */\nfunction delegateRef(args) {\n  if (Array.isArray(args)) return args.slice(0, 3).filter(Boolean).join('/');\n  if (args && typeof args === 'object') {\n    const { space, agent, action } = args;\n    return [space, agent, action].filter(Boolean).join('/');\n  }\n  return String(args);\n}\n\n/** The prose THING showed the user: display() descriptors + the final assistant text. */\nexport function textOf(events) {\n  const out = [];\n  for (const e of events) {\n    if (e.type === 'display') {\n      const d = e.descriptor;\n      const s =\n        typeof d === 'string'\n          ? d\n          : (d?.props?.text ?? d?.props?.children ?? d?.props?.content ?? JSON.stringify(d));\n      out.push(typeof s === 'string' ? s : JSON.stringify(s));\n    }\n  }\n  return out.join('\\n');\n}\n\n/** The LAST thing THING displayed — its final reply for this turn (see `turn().lastText`). */\nexport function lastTextOf(events) {\n  for (let i = events.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n    const e = events[i];\n    if (e.type !== 'display') continue;\n    const d = e.descriptor;\n    const s =\n      typeof d === 'string'\n        ? d\n        : (d?.props?.text ?? d?.props?.children ?? d?.props?.content ?? JSON.stringify(d));\n    const out = typeof s === 'string' ? s : JSON.stringify(s);\n    if (out && out.trim()) return out;\n  }\n  return '';\n}\n\n/** Approve every consent card; leave other asks for the scenario. */\nexport const approveAllConsent = (descriptor) =>\n  descriptor?.type === 'ConsentCard' ? true : undefined;\n/** Deny every consent card (for the denial branch of the consent scenario). */\nexport const denyAllConsent = (descriptor) =>\n  descriptor?.type === 'ConsentCard' ? false : undefined;\n","numLines":477,"startLine":1,"totalLines":477}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_BTXb2pl0g6NTuNTsynhIbAbd","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/**\n2\t * Pod HTTP client — the compute pod IS the app (see sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/serve.ts).\n3\t *\n4\t * The pod itself does no auth: Envoy validates the gateway JWT at the edge and routes on the\n5\t * `sub` claim to `lmthing.user-<id>.svc`. So every call here just carries the bearer token and\n6\t * talks to the chat origin. Locally (`lmthing serve`) pass base=http://localhost:8080 and no token.\n7\t */\n8\timport { LOCAL, restartLocalServer } from './local.mjs';\n9\t\n10\t/**\n11\t * A pod that is scaling from zero, rolling a new image, or sitting behind a blipping gateway does\n12\t * not always answer with a *response* — the connection itself fails (undici's 10s\n13\t * `ConnectTimeoutError`, `ECONNRESET`, `socket hang up`, a DNS `EAI_AGAIN`). Those surface as a\n14\t * bare `TypeError: fetch failed`, which is NOT an HTTP status and so slipped past every\n15\t * `{waking:true}`/504 retry below — one connect timeout to lmthing.chat killed a multi-hour run\n16\t * with an uncaught exception. Treat a transient transport fault exactly like a `waking` answer:\n17\t * back off and retry. A non-transient error (a bad URL, an aborted body) still throws at once.\n18\t */\n19\tconst TRANSIENT = /fetch failed|ConnectTimeout|UND_ERR|ECONNRESET|ECONNREFUSED|EAI_AGAIN|socket hang up|network|terminated|other side closed/i;\n20\t\n21\texport async function fetchResilient(url, init, { tries = 40, waitMs = 3000 } = {}) {\n22\t  for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n23\t    try {\n24\t      return await fetch(url, init);\n25\t    } catch (e) {\n26\t      const msg = `${e?.message ?? e} ${e?.cause?.code ?? ''} ${e?.cause?.message ?? ''}`;\n27\t      if (!TRANSIENT.test(msg) || attempt >= tries) throw e;\n28\t      await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, waitMs));\n29\t    }\n30\t  }\n31\t}\n32\t\n33\texport class Pod {\n34\t  /**\n35\t   * @param {object} o\n36\t   * @param {string} o.base      the pod/API origin (prod: https://lmthing.chat)\n37\t   * @param {string} [o.token]   gateway JWT (Envoy routes on its `sub` claim)\n38\t   * @param {string} [o.appBase] the SERVED-APP origin. In prod the app is NOT reachable under\n39\t   *   `<chat>/app/<id>/` — Envoy hands `/app/*` on the chat host to the static web SPA (nginx),\n40\t   *   which answers a GET with the SPA *shell* (a 200 `<!doctype>` that is not the app at all —\n41\t   *   a scenario asserting only \"200 + <!doctype\" false-passes) and a POST with **405**. The app\n42\t   *   is root-mounted on lmthing.app (`/<project>/`, `/<project>/api/<route>` — serve.ts's\n43\t   *   \"Project-app ROOT mount\"). Locally there is no split host, so apps stay under `/app/<id>/`.\n44\t   */\n45\t  constructor({ base, token, appBase }) {\n46\t    this.base = base;\n47\t    this.token = token;\n48\t    this.appBase = appBase ?? process.env.LM_APP_BASE ?? (/lmthing\\.chat/.test(base) ? 'https://lmthing.app' : base);\n49\t    /** true when the app has its own host → root mount (no `/app` prefix). */\n50\t    this.appRootMounted = this.appBase !== this.base;\n51\t  }\n52\t\n53\t  /** The origin+prefix the SERVED app actually lives at (see `appBase`). */\n54\t  appOrigin(projectId) {\n55\t    return this.appRootMounted\n56\t      ? `${this.appBase}/${projectId}`\n57\t      : `${this.base}/app/${projectId}`;\n58\t  }\n59\t\n60\t  /** Absolute-URL variant of `req` (the served app is on a different origin than /api/*). */\n61\t  async reqAbs(method, url, body) {\n62\t    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n63\t      const res = await fetchResilient(url, {\n64\t        method,\n65\t        headers: {\n66\t          ...(body !== undefined ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n67\t          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n68\t        },\n69\t        ...(body !== undefined ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n70\t      });\n71\t      const text = await res.text();\n72\t      let parsed = text;\n73\t      try {\n74\t        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n75\t      } catch {\n76\t        /* html / raw */\n77\t      }\n78\t      // The activator MARKS its own response (`{waking:true}`) whatever status it uses (503/504),\n79\t      // so key on that marker — never on a bare 503, which for an app route is a real verdict.\n80\t      const waking =\n81\t        res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n82\t      if (waking && attempt < 100) {\n83\t        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n84\t        continue;\n85\t      }\n86\t      return { status: res.status, body: parsed };\n87\t    }\n88\t  }\n89\t\n90\t  async req(method, path, body, { raw = false } = {}) {\n91\t    // A scaled-to-zero pod answers with `504 {waking:true}` while the Envoy activator boots\n92\t    // it; that is a transient, not the endpoint's verdict. Retry idempotent-ish calls until\n93\t    // the pod is warm (bounded), so a read that lands on a cold pod self-heals instead of\n94\t    // throwing a spurious failure mid-scenario.\n95\t    //\n96\t    // The budget is minutes, not seconds. A pod that is ROLLING (a new image) or whose single\n97\t    // Node thread is stalled inside a long authoring turn keeps answering `waking` well past a\n98\t    // minute — the old 20×3s ≈ 60s gave up and threw `POST /api/sessions → 503 {waking:true}`,\n99\t    // killing a multi-hour run over a transient the harness was written to absorb.\n100\t    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n101\t      const res = await fetchResilient(`${this.base}${path}`, {\n102\t        method,\n103\t        headers: {\n104\t          ...(body !== undefined ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n105\t          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n106\t        },\n107\t        ...(body !== undefined ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n108\t      });\n109\t      const text = await res.text();\n110\t      let parsed = text;\n111\t      try {\n112\t        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n113\t      } catch {\n114\t        /* raw text (e.g. an ASCII state tree) */\n115\t      }\n116\t      // The activator MARKS its own response (`{waking:true}`) whatever status it uses (503/504),\n117\t      // so key on that marker — never on a bare 503, which for an app route is a real verdict.\n118\t      const waking =\n119\t        res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n120\t      if (waking && attempt < 100) {\n121\t        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n122\t        continue;\n123\t      }\n124\t      if (!res.ok && !raw) {\n125\t        const err = new Error(`${method} ${path} → ${res.status}: ${text.slice(0, 400)}`);\n126\t        err.status = res.status;\n127\t        err.body = parsed;\n128\t        throw err;\n129\t      }\n130\t      return raw ? { status: res.status, body: parsed } : parsed;\n131\t    }\n132\t  }\n133\t\n134\t  // ── projects ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n135\t  listProjects = () => this.req('GET', '/api/projects');\n136\t  createProject = (name) => this.req('POST', '/api/projects', { name });\n137\t  deleteProject = (id) => this.req('DELETE', `/api/projects/${id}`);\n138\t  listSpaces = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/spaces`);\n139\t  listIntegrations = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/integrations`);\n140\t  projectSessions = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/sessions`);\n141\t\n142\t  // ── files (the whole point: assert what the agents actually WROTE) ───────\n143\t  fsTree = () => this.req('GET', '/api/fs/tree');\n144\t  readFile = (path) => this.req('GET', `/api/fs/read?path=${encodeURIComponent(path)}`);\n145\t  writeFile = (path, content) => this.req('PUT', '/api/fs/write', { path, content });\n146\t\n147\t  /** Read one authored file of a project (`<project>/pages/_layout.tsx`, `api/…`) — assert what the agent WROTE. */\n148\t  async readProjectFile(projectId, rel) {\n149\t    const r = await this.readFile(`${projectId}/${rel}`).catch(() => null);\n150\t    return typeof r === 'string' ? r : (r?.content ?? '');\n151\t  }\n152\t\n153\t  // ── store ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n154\t  storeSpaces = () => this.req('GET', '/api/store/spaces');\n155\t  installSpace = (spaceId, projectId = 'user', force = false) =>\n156\t    this.req('POST', '/api/store/spaces/install', { spaceId, projectId, force });\n157\t  storeApps = () => this.req('GET', '/api/apps');\n158\t  installApp = (appId, projectId, force = false) =>\n159\t    this.req('POST', '/api/apps/install', { appId, ...(projectId ? { projectId } : {}), force });\n160\t\n161\t  // ── project-app runtime ─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n162\t  appManifest = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/app`);\n163\t  appBuild = (projectId) => this.req('POST', `/api/projects/${projectId}/app/build`);\n164\t  appData = (projectId, table) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/app/data/${table}`);\n165\t  /** GET the SERVED app page — on its real origin (see `appBase`), not the SPA shell. */\n166\t  appPage = (projectId, path = '') => this.reqAbs('GET', `${this.appOrigin(projectId)}/${path}`);\n167\t\n168\t  // ── hooks & events ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n169\t  /** List every loaded hook across projects (`GET /api/hooks`). */\n170\t  listHooks = () => this.req('GET', '/api/hooks');\n171\t  /**\n172\t   * Call an app's OWN API route — the routes its pages actually fetch, on the app's real origin\n173\t   * (`<app-host>/<project>/api/<route>`). This is the layer the user sees: a page whose data API\n174\t   * returns rows can still render zeros because its own aggregation route 500s.\n175\t   */\n176\t  appApi = (projectId, route, body, method = 'POST') =>\n177\t    this.reqAbs(method, `${this.appOrigin(projectId)}/api/${String(route).replace(/^\\//, '')}`, body);\n178\t  /** The one authoritative hook-run path (crond, boot catch-up and Studio all use it).\n179\t   *  The slug is a single path segment and may contain `:`/`@` (space hooks are\n180\t   *  `<spaceId>:<base>`; emitters are `@emitter:<scope>:<name>`) — encode it. */\n181\t  runHook = (projectId, slug) =>\n182\t    this.req('POST', `/api/projects/${projectId}/hooks/${encodeURIComponent(slug)}/run`, {});\n183\t  /** Run a cron emitter def by its pseudo-slug (`@emitter:<scope>:<name>`). */\n184\t  runEmitter = (projectId, scope, name) => this.runHook(projectId, `@emitter:${scope}:${name}`);\n185\t\n186\t  /**\n187\t   * Deliver an inbound webhook exactly as an external provider would.\n188\t   * `headers` carries the provider's signature headers — the pod verifies BEFORE emit.\n189\t   *\n190\t   * NOTE the bearer token: in prod the pod is reached through Envoy, which routes on the\n191\t   * gateway JWT's `sub` claim — without it the edge answers `401 Jwt is missing` and the\n192\t   * request never reaches the pod. The real public path (gateway `/api/inbound/<token>/<path>`)\n193\t   * is a 202 fire-and-forget broker that hides the pod's own status code, so a scenario that\n194\t   * needs to assert 200/401/404 + `{events:n}` must deliver to the pod directly. The pod\n195\t   * itself does no auth: verification is the provider signature, exactly as in production.\n196\t   */\n197\t  async inbound(path, body, headers = {}) {\n198\t    const payload = typeof body === 'string' ? body : JSON.stringify(body);\n199\t    // A scaled-to-zero pod answers the FIRST hit with `504 {waking:true}` (the Envoy\n200\t    // instant-wake activator) while it boots — that is not the def's real verdict. Retry\n201\t    // the exact same signed bytes until the woken pod actually runs verify→emit. The body\n202\t    // is byte-identical, but inbound dedupe only kicks in AFTER a successful verify, so a\n203\t    // retry of a request the pod never processed is not deduped.\n204\t    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n205\t      const res = await fetchResilient(`${this.base}/api/inbound/${path}`, {\n206\t        method: 'POST',\n207\t        headers: {\n208\t          'content-type': 'application/json',\n209\t          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n210\t          ...headers,\n211\t        },\n212\t        body: payload,\n213\t      });\n214\t      const text = await res.text();\n215\t      let parsed = text;\n216\t      try {\n217\t        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n218\t      } catch {\n219\t        /* raw */\n220\t      }\n221\t      const waking = res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n222\t      if (!waking || attempt >= 100) return { status: res.status, body: parsed };\n223\t      await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n224\t    }\n225\t  }\n226\t\n227\t  // ── uploads (chat attachments) ──────────────────────────────────────────\n228\t  /**\n229\t   * The mediaType decides the pod's ROUTE, not just a label: `image/*` goes to system-vision,\n230\t   * `audio/*` is transcribed at ingest, everything else goes to system-files. So a `.mp3` sent as\n231\t   * `application/octet-stream` is never transcribed, and a scenario asserting \"a spoken-only fact\n232\t   * reached a row\" fails for a reason that has nothing to do with the product. Every fixture type the\n233\t   * scenarios actually upload must be in this table.\n234\t   */\n235\t  static MEDIA_TYPES = {\n236\t    '.md': 'text/markdown',\n237\t    '.txt': 'text/plain',\n238\t    '.csv': 'text/csv',\n239\t    '.json': 'application/json',\n240\t    '.pdf': 'application/pdf',\n241\t    '.jpg': 'image/jpeg',\n242\t    '.jpeg': 'image/jpeg',\n243\t    '.png': 'image/png',\n244\t    '.webp': 'image/webp',\n245\t    '.gif': 'image/gif',\n246\t    '.mp3': 'audio/mpeg',\n247\t    '.m4a': 'audio/mp4',\n248\t    '.wav': 'audio/wav',\n249\t    '.ogg': 'audio/ogg',\n250\t    '.webm': 'audio/webm',\n251\t    '.xlsx': 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet',\n252\t    '.xls': 'application/vnd.ms-excel',\n253\t    '.docx': 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document',\n254\t  };\n255\t\n256\t  /**\n257\t   * Upload a local file as a chat attachment (the UI's \"load a file\" action).\n258\t   * `POST /api/uploads` takes base64 + mediaType and returns an AttachmentRef\n259\t   * (`{id, kind, mediaType, filename?, url}`) that a message then references by id.\n260\t   * Pair with `ThingSession.sendWithAttachments()` (WS path — HTTP /message drops attachments).\n261\t   *\n262\t   * Throws on an unknown extension rather than silently sending `application/octet-stream` — a\n263\t   * misrouted attachment turns a real product failure into a green test (see MEDIA_TYPES).\n264\t   */\n265\t  async upload(filePath, { mediaType, filename } = {}) {\n266\t    const { readFileSync } = await import('node:fs');\n267\t    const { basename, extname } = await import('node:path');\n268\t    const bytes = readFileSync(filePath);\n269\t    const ext = extname(filePath).toLowerCase();\n270\t    const mt = mediaType ?? Pod.MEDIA_TYPES[ext];\n271\t    if (!mt) {\n272\t      throw new Error(\n273\t        `upload(${basename(filePath)}): no mediaType known for \"${ext}\" — pass { mediaType } explicitly ` +\n274\t          `or add it to Pod.MEDIA_TYPES. Guessing octet-stream would misroute it (no vision, no transcription).`,\n275\t      );\n276\t    }\n277\t    const ref = await this.req('POST', '/api/uploads', {\n278\t      filename: filename ?? basename(filePath),\n279\t      mediaType: mt,\n280\t      data: bytes.toString('base64'),\n281\t    });\n282\t    return ref;\n283\t  }\n284\t\n285\t  // ── accounting ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n286\t  /** Pod-global token/cost ledger — includes the DELEGATE tree, not just top-level turns. */\n287\t  sessionLedger = () => this.req('GET', '/api/session-ledger');\n288\t  /** The gateway's spend-window report, as the pod sees it. */\n289\t  budget = () => this.req('GET', '/api/budget');\n290\t\n291\t  // ── env / lifecycle ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n292\t  getEnv = () => this.req('GET', '/api/env');\n293\t  /**\n294\t   * Restart the pod process (used by the auto-resume scenario). The pod exits ~100ms later.\n295\t   *\n296\t   * In prod, Kubernetes brings it straight back. LOCALLY, NOTHING DOES — `POST /api/restart` just\n297\t   * kills the one shared `lmthing serve` and leaves it dead, hanging this lane AND every sibling\n298\t   * lane on the same server (found the hard way: S06's Act XIII took the whole local pod down\n299\t   * mid-run). So on the local target we must bring it back up ourselves — which is also the truer\n300\t   * reproduction of the edge this Act exists to test: the process really does die and really does\n301\t   * come back, and the session must survive it.\n302\t   */\n303\t  restart = async () => {\n304\t    if (!LOCAL) return this.req('POST', '/api/restart', {}).catch(() => ({ ok: true }));\n305\t    await this.req('POST', '/api/restart', {}).catch(() => ({ ok: true }));\n306\t    await restartLocalServer();\n307\t    return { ok: true, local: true };\n308\t  };\n309\t}\n310\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f21d2fda-94ab-442d-8f32-017580283d3b","uuid":"a01fe76c-4052-4ed3-8396-7070df6beb13","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:53:17.043Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/lib/pod.mjs","content":"/**\n * Pod HTTP client — the compute pod IS the app (see sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/serve.ts).\n *\n * The pod itself does no auth: Envoy validates the gateway JWT at the edge and routes on the\n * `sub` claim to `lmthing.user-<id>.svc`. So every call here just carries the bearer token and\n * talks to the chat origin. Locally (`lmthing serve`) pass base=http://localhost:8080 and no token.\n */\nimport { LOCAL, restartLocalServer } from './local.mjs';\n\n/**\n * A pod that is scaling from zero, rolling a new image, or sitting behind a blipping gateway does\n * not always answer with a *response* — the connection itself fails (undici's 10s\n * `ConnectTimeoutError`, `ECONNRESET`, `socket hang up`, a DNS `EAI_AGAIN`). Those surface as a\n * bare `TypeError: fetch failed`, which is NOT an HTTP status and so slipped past every\n * `{waking:true}`/504 retry below — one connect timeout to lmthing.chat killed a multi-hour run\n * with an uncaught exception. Treat a transient transport fault exactly like a `waking` answer:\n * back off and retry. A non-transient error (a bad URL, an aborted body) still throws at once.\n */\nconst TRANSIENT = /fetch failed|ConnectTimeout|UND_ERR|ECONNRESET|ECONNREFUSED|EAI_AGAIN|socket hang up|network|terminated|other side closed/i;\n\nexport async function fetchResilient(url, init, { tries = 40, waitMs = 3000 } = {}) {\n  for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n    try {\n      return await fetch(url, init);\n    } catch (e) {\n      const msg = `${e?.message ?? e} ${e?.cause?.code ?? ''} ${e?.cause?.message ?? ''}`;\n      if (!TRANSIENT.test(msg) || attempt >= tries) throw e;\n      await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, waitMs));\n    }\n  }\n}\n\nexport class Pod {\n  /**\n   * @param {object} o\n   * @param {string} o.base      the pod/API origin (prod: https://lmthing.chat)\n   * @param {string} [o.token]   gateway JWT (Envoy routes on its `sub` claim)\n   * @param {string} [o.appBase] the SERVED-APP origin. In prod the app is NOT reachable under\n   *   `<chat>/app/<id>/` — Envoy hands `/app/*` on the chat host to the static web SPA (nginx),\n   *   which answers a GET with the SPA *shell* (a 200 `<!doctype>` that is not the app at all —\n   *   a scenario asserting only \"200 + <!doctype\" false-passes) and a POST with **405**. The app\n   *   is root-mounted on lmthing.app (`/<project>/`, `/<project>/api/<route>` — serve.ts's\n   *   \"Project-app ROOT mount\"). Locally there is no split host, so apps stay under `/app/<id>/`.\n   */\n  constructor({ base, token, appBase }) {\n    this.base = base;\n    this.token = token;\n    this.appBase = appBase ?? process.env.LM_APP_BASE ?? (/lmthing\\.chat/.test(base) ? 'https://lmthing.app' : base);\n    /** true when the app has its own host → root mount (no `/app` prefix). */\n    this.appRootMounted = this.appBase !== this.base;\n  }\n\n  /** The origin+prefix the SERVED app actually lives at (see `appBase`). */\n  appOrigin(projectId) {\n    return this.appRootMounted\n      ? `${this.appBase}/${projectId}`\n      : `${this.base}/app/${projectId}`;\n  }\n\n  /** Absolute-URL variant of `req` (the served app is on a different origin than /api/*). */\n  async reqAbs(method, url, body) {\n    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n      const res = await fetchResilient(url, {\n        method,\n        headers: {\n          ...(body !== undefined ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n        },\n        ...(body !== undefined ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n      });\n      const text = await res.text();\n      let parsed = text;\n      try {\n        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n      } catch {\n        /* html / raw */\n      }\n      // The activator MARKS its own response (`{waking:true}`) whatever status it uses (503/504),\n      // so key on that marker — never on a bare 503, which for an app route is a real verdict.\n      const waking =\n        res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n      if (waking && attempt < 100) {\n        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n        continue;\n      }\n      return { status: res.status, body: parsed };\n    }\n  }\n\n  async req(method, path, body, { raw = false } = {}) {\n    // A scaled-to-zero pod answers with `504 {waking:true}` while the Envoy activator boots\n    // it; that is a transient, not the endpoint's verdict. Retry idempotent-ish calls until\n    // the pod is warm (bounded), so a read that lands on a cold pod self-heals instead of\n    // throwing a spurious failure mid-scenario.\n    //\n    // The budget is minutes, not seconds. A pod that is ROLLING (a new image) or whose single\n    // Node thread is stalled inside a long authoring turn keeps answering `waking` well past a\n    // minute — the old 20×3s ≈ 60s gave up and threw `POST /api/sessions → 503 {waking:true}`,\n    // killing a multi-hour run over a transient the harness was written to absorb.\n    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n      const res = await fetchResilient(`${this.base}${path}`, {\n        method,\n        headers: {\n          ...(body !== undefined ? { 'content-type': 'application/json' } : {}),\n          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n        },\n        ...(body !== undefined ? { body: JSON.stringify(body) } : {}),\n      });\n      const text = await res.text();\n      let parsed = text;\n      try {\n        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n      } catch {\n        /* raw text (e.g. an ASCII state tree) */\n      }\n      // The activator MARKS its own response (`{waking:true}`) whatever status it uses (503/504),\n      // so key on that marker — never on a bare 503, which for an app route is a real verdict.\n      const waking =\n        res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n      if (waking && attempt < 100) {\n        await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n        continue;\n      }\n      if (!res.ok && !raw) {\n        const err = new Error(`${method} ${path} → ${res.status}: ${text.slice(0, 400)}`);\n        err.status = res.status;\n        err.body = parsed;\n        throw err;\n      }\n      return raw ? { status: res.status, body: parsed } : parsed;\n    }\n  }\n\n  // ── projects ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  listProjects = () => this.req('GET', '/api/projects');\n  createProject = (name) => this.req('POST', '/api/projects', { name });\n  deleteProject = (id) => this.req('DELETE', `/api/projects/${id}`);\n  listSpaces = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/spaces`);\n  listIntegrations = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/integrations`);\n  projectSessions = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/sessions`);\n\n  // ── files (the whole point: assert what the agents actually WROTE) ───────\n  fsTree = () => this.req('GET', '/api/fs/tree');\n  readFile = (path) => this.req('GET', `/api/fs/read?path=${encodeURIComponent(path)}`);\n  writeFile = (path, content) => this.req('PUT', '/api/fs/write', { path, content });\n\n  /** Read one authored file of a project (`<project>/pages/_layout.tsx`, `api/…`) — assert what the agent WROTE. */\n  async readProjectFile(projectId, rel) {\n    const r = await this.readFile(`${projectId}/${rel}`).catch(() => null);\n    return typeof r === 'string' ? r : (r?.content ?? '');\n  }\n\n  // ── store ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  storeSpaces = () => this.req('GET', '/api/store/spaces');\n  installSpace = (spaceId, projectId = 'user', force = false) =>\n    this.req('POST', '/api/store/spaces/install', { spaceId, projectId, force });\n  storeApps = () => this.req('GET', '/api/apps');\n  installApp = (appId, projectId, force = false) =>\n    this.req('POST', '/api/apps/install', { appId, ...(projectId ? { projectId } : {}), force });\n\n  // ── project-app runtime ─────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  appManifest = (projectId) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/app`);\n  appBuild = (projectId) => this.req('POST', `/api/projects/${projectId}/app/build`);\n  appData = (projectId, table) => this.req('GET', `/api/projects/${projectId}/app/data/${table}`);\n  /** GET the SERVED app page — on its real origin (see `appBase`), not the SPA shell. */\n  appPage = (projectId, path = '') => this.reqAbs('GET', `${this.appOrigin(projectId)}/${path}`);\n\n  // ── hooks & events ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  /** List every loaded hook across projects (`GET /api/hooks`). */\n  listHooks = () => this.req('GET', '/api/hooks');\n  /**\n   * Call an app's OWN API route — the routes its pages actually fetch, on the app's real origin\n   * (`<app-host>/<project>/api/<route>`). This is the layer the user sees: a page whose data API\n   * returns rows can still render zeros because its own aggregation route 500s.\n   */\n  appApi = (projectId, route, body, method = 'POST') =>\n    this.reqAbs(method, `${this.appOrigin(projectId)}/api/${String(route).replace(/^\\//, '')}`, body);\n  /** The one authoritative hook-run path (crond, boot catch-up and Studio all use it).\n   *  The slug is a single path segment and may contain `:`/`@` (space hooks are\n   *  `<spaceId>:<base>`; emitters are `@emitter:<scope>:<name>`) — encode it. */\n  runHook = (projectId, slug) =>\n    this.req('POST', `/api/projects/${projectId}/hooks/${encodeURIComponent(slug)}/run`, {});\n  /** Run a cron emitter def by its pseudo-slug (`@emitter:<scope>:<name>`). */\n  runEmitter = (projectId, scope, name) => this.runHook(projectId, `@emitter:${scope}:${name}`);\n\n  /**\n   * Deliver an inbound webhook exactly as an external provider would.\n   * `headers` carries the provider's signature headers — the pod verifies BEFORE emit.\n   *\n   * NOTE the bearer token: in prod the pod is reached through Envoy, which routes on the\n   * gateway JWT's `sub` claim — without it the edge answers `401 Jwt is missing` and the\n   * request never reaches the pod. The real public path (gateway `/api/inbound/<token>/<path>`)\n   * is a 202 fire-and-forget broker that hides the pod's own status code, so a scenario that\n   * needs to assert 200/401/404 + `{events:n}` must deliver to the pod directly. The pod\n   * itself does no auth: verification is the provider signature, exactly as in production.\n   */\n  async inbound(path, body, headers = {}) {\n    const payload = typeof body === 'string' ? body : JSON.stringify(body);\n    // A scaled-to-zero pod answers the FIRST hit with `504 {waking:true}` (the Envoy\n    // instant-wake activator) while it boots — that is not the def's real verdict. Retry\n    // the exact same signed bytes until the woken pod actually runs verify→emit. The body\n    // is byte-identical, but inbound dedupe only kicks in AFTER a successful verify, so a\n    // retry of a request the pod never processed is not deduped.\n    for (let attempt = 0; ; attempt++) {\n      const res = await fetchResilient(`${this.base}/api/inbound/${path}`, {\n        method: 'POST',\n        headers: {\n          'content-type': 'application/json',\n          ...(this.token ? { authorization: `Bearer ${this.token}` } : {}),\n          ...headers,\n        },\n        body: payload,\n      });\n      const text = await res.text();\n      let parsed = text;\n      try {\n        parsed = JSON.parse(text);\n      } catch {\n        /* raw */\n      }\n      const waking = res.status === 504 || (parsed && typeof parsed === 'object' && parsed.waking === true);\n      if (!waking || attempt >= 100) return { status: res.status, body: parsed };\n      await new Promise((r) => setTimeout(r, 3000));\n    }\n  }\n\n  // ── uploads (chat attachments) ──────────────────────────────────────────\n  /**\n   * The mediaType decides the pod's ROUTE, not just a label: `image/*` goes to system-vision,\n   * `audio/*` is transcribed at ingest, everything else goes to system-files. So a `.mp3` sent as\n   * `application/octet-stream` is never transcribed, and a scenario asserting \"a spoken-only fact\n   * reached a row\" fails for a reason that has nothing to do with the product. Every fixture type the\n   * scenarios actually upload must be in this table.\n   */\n  static MEDIA_TYPES = {\n    '.md': 'text/markdown',\n    '.txt': 'text/plain',\n    '.csv': 'text/csv',\n    '.json': 'application/json',\n    '.pdf': 'application/pdf',\n    '.jpg': 'image/jpeg',\n    '.jpeg': 'image/jpeg',\n    '.png': 'image/png',\n    '.webp': 'image/webp',\n    '.gif': 'image/gif',\n    '.mp3': 'audio/mpeg',\n    '.m4a': 'audio/mp4',\n    '.wav': 'audio/wav',\n    '.ogg': 'audio/ogg',\n    '.webm': 'audio/webm',\n    '.xlsx': 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.spreadsheetml.sheet',\n    '.xls': 'application/vnd.ms-excel',\n    '.docx': 'application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.wordprocessingml.document',\n  };\n\n  /**\n   * Upload a local file as a chat attachment (the UI's \"load a file\" action).\n   * `POST /api/uploads` takes base64 + mediaType and returns an AttachmentRef\n   * (`{id, kind, mediaType, filename?, url}`) that a message then references by id.\n   * Pair with `ThingSession.sendWithAttachments()` (WS path — HTTP /message drops attachments).\n   *\n   * Throws on an unknown extension rather than silently sending `application/octet-stream` — a\n   * misrouted attachment turns a real product failure into a green test (see MEDIA_TYPES).\n   */\n  async upload(filePath, { mediaType, filename } = {}) {\n    const { readFileSync } = await import('node:fs');\n    const { basename, extname } = await import('node:path');\n    const bytes = readFileSync(filePath);\n    const ext = extname(filePath).toLowerCase();\n    const mt = mediaType ?? Pod.MEDIA_TYPES[ext];\n    if (!mt) {\n      throw new Error(\n        `upload(${basename(filePath)}): no mediaType known for \"${ext}\" — pass { mediaType } explicitly ` +\n          `or add it to Pod.MEDIA_TYPES. Guessing octet-stream would misroute it (no vision, no transcription).`,\n      );\n    }\n    const ref = await this.req('POST', '/api/uploads', {\n      filename: filename ?? basename(filePath),\n      mediaType: mt,\n      data: bytes.toString('base64'),\n    });\n    return ref;\n  }\n\n  // ── accounting ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  /** Pod-global token/cost ledger — includes the DELEGATE tree, not just top-level turns. */\n  sessionLedger = () => this.req('GET', '/api/session-ledger');\n  /** The gateway's spend-window report, as the pod sees it. */\n  budget = () => this.req('GET', '/api/budget');\n\n  // ── env / lifecycle ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────\n  getEnv = () => this.req('GET', '/api/env');\n  /**\n   * Restart the pod process (used by the auto-resume scenario). The pod exits ~100ms later.\n   *\n   * In prod, Kubernetes brings it straight back. LOCALLY, NOTHING DOES — `POST /api/restart` just\n   * kills the one shared `lmthing serve` and leaves it dead, hanging this lane AND every sibling\n   * lane on the same server (found the hard way: S06's Act XIII took the whole local pod down\n   * mid-run). So on the local target we must bring it back up ourselves — which is also the truer\n   * reproduction of the edge this Act exists to test: the process really does die and really does\n   * come back, and the session must survive it.\n   */\n  restart = async () => {\n    if (!LOCAL) return this.req('POST', '/api/restart', {}).catch(() => ({ ok: true }));\n    await this.req('POST', '/api/restart', {}).catch(() => ({ ok: true }));\n    await restartLocalServer();\n    return { ok: true, local: true };\n  };\n}\n","numLines":310,"startLine":1,"totalLines":310}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_MR5sUG8USbBwTfFoOpUYW6Nw","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t/**\n2\t * Scenario report builder — turns a run into the \"Actual results\" table that gets pasted back\n3\t * into the scenario's markdown file, so every run is reproducible and reviewable.\n4\t *\n5\t * A scenario is a list of steps; each step has an EXPECTED outcome declared up front and an\n6\t * ACTUAL outcome recorded at run time. `check()` records a pass/fail against an expectation;\n7\t * `note()` records an observation. Nothing throws by default — a scenario is meant to run to the\n8\t * end and report every failure, not die on the first one.\n9\t */\n10\timport { mkdirSync, writeFileSync } from 'node:fs';\n11\timport { dirname } from 'node:path';\n12\t\n13\texport class Report {\n14\t  constructor(id, title) {\n15\t    this.id = id;\n16\t    this.title = title;\n17\t    this.started = Date.now();\n18\t    this.steps = [];\n19\t    this.current = null;\n20\t    this.metrics = [];\n21\t    this.issues = [];\n22\t  }\n23\t\n24\t  /** Begin a step. `expected` is the contract this step is asserting. */\n25\t  step(name, expected) {\n26\t    this.current = { name, expected, checks: [], notes: [], started: Date.now() };\n27\t    this.steps.push(this.current);\n28\t    console.log(`\\n── ${this.id} · ${name}\\n   expect: ${expected}`);\n29\t    return this.current;\n30\t  }\n31\t\n32\t  check(label, pass, actual = '') {\n33\t    const rec = { label, pass: !!pass, actual: String(actual).slice(0, 500) };\n34\t    (this.current?.checks ?? (this.current = this.step('(unnamed)', '')).checks).push(rec);\n35\t    console.log(`   ${pass ? '✓' : '✗'} ${label}${actual ? ` — ${String(actual).slice(0, 160)}` : ''}`);\n36\t    return rec.pass;\n37\t  }\n38\t\n39\t  note(text) {\n40\t    this.current?.notes.push(String(text));\n41\t    console.log(`   · ${text}`);\n42\t  }\n43\t\n44\t  /** A row for the performance table (turn timings, token burn, event counts). */\n45\t  metric(name, value, unit = '') {\n46\t    this.metrics.push({ name, value, unit });\n47\t    console.log(`   ▸ ${name}: ${value}${unit}`);\n48\t  }\n49\t\n50\t  /** A bug found during the run. `fix` is filled in once the subagent has fixed it. */\n51\t  issue(title, detail, { severity = 'bug', fix = null } = {}) {\n52\t    this.issues.push({ title, detail: String(detail).slice(0, 2000), severity, fix });\n53\t    console.log(`   ⚠ ISSUE [${severity}] ${title}`);\n54\t  }\n55\t\n56\t  get passed() {\n57\t    return this.steps.every((s) => s.checks.every((c) => c.pass));\n58\t  }\n59\t\n60\t  /**\n61\t   * Did the step CURRENTLY being recorded pass?\n62\t   *\n63\t   * `passed` is the whole report; an Act's checkpoint must record the ACT. Writing\n64\t   * `cp.acts.VIII = { passed: report.passed }` after a batch where Act VII failed marked Act VIII\n65\t   * failed too — all three of its checks were green. A checkpoint that lies about which Act broke\n66\t   * is worse than no checkpoint: the next run re-debugs the wrong Act.\n67\t   */\n68\t  get stepPassed() {\n69\t    return (this.current?.checks ?? []).every((c) => c.pass);\n70\t  }\n71\t\n72\t  summary() {\n73\t    const all = this.steps.flatMap((s) => s.checks);\n74\t    return { total: all.length, passed: all.filter((c) => c.pass).length, issues: this.issues.length };\n75\t  }\n76\t\n77\t  /** Render the \"Actual results\" markdown that gets appended to the scenario doc. */\n78\t  markdown() {\n79\t    const s = this.summary();\n80\t    const mins = ((Date.now() - this.started) / 60_000).toFixed(1);\n81\t    const L = [\n82\t      `## Actual results — run ${new Date(this.started).toISOString()}`,\n83\t      ``,\n84\t      `**Verdict: ${this.passed ? '✅ PASS' : '❌ FAIL'}** · ${s.passed}/${s.total} checks · ` +\n85\t        `${s.issues} issue(s) found · ${mins} min wall clock`,\n86\t      ``,\n87\t    ];\n88\t    for (const st of this.steps) {\n89\t      L.push(`### ${st.name}`, ``, `*Expected:* ${st.expected}`, ``);\n90\t      if (st.checks.length) {\n91\t        L.push(`| Check | Result | Actual |`, `|---|---|---|`);\n92\t        for (const c of st.checks) {\n93\t          const actual = c.actual.replace(/\\|/g, '\\\\|').replace(/\\n/g, ' ');\n94\t          L.push(`| ${c.label} | ${c.pass ? '✅' : '❌'} | ${actual || '—'} |`);\n95\t        }\n96\t        L.push('');\n97\t      }\n98\t      for (const n of st.notes) L.push(`> ${n.replace(/\\n/g, '\\n> ')}`, '');\n99\t    }\n100\t    if (this.metrics.length) {\n101\t      L.push(`### Performance`, ``, `| Metric | Value |`, `|---|---|`);\n102\t      for (const m of this.metrics) L.push(`| ${m.name} | ${m.value}${m.unit} |`);\n103\t      L.push('');\n104\t    }\n105\t    if (this.issues.length) {\n106\t      L.push(`### Issues found`, ``);\n107\t      for (const i of this.issues) {\n108\t        L.push(\n109\t          `#### ${i.severity}: ${i.title}`,\n110\t          ``,\n111\t          i.detail,\n112\t          ``,\n113\t          i.fix ? `**Fix:** ${i.fix}` : `**Fix:** _pending_`,\n114\t          ``,\n115\t        );\n116\t      }\n117\t    }\n118\t    return L.join('\\n');\n119\t  }\n120\t\n121\t  save(path) {\n122\t    mkdirSync(dirname(path), { recursive: true });\n123\t    writeFileSync(path, this.markdown());\n124\t    console.log(`\\n📄 ${path}  (${this.passed ? 'PASS' : 'FAIL'})`);\n125\t    return path;\n126\t  }\n127\t\n128\t  /** Dump the raw trace for post-mortems — a scenario report is only as good as its evidence. */\n129\t  saveTrace(path, session) {\n130\t    mkdirSync(dirname(path), { recursive: true });\n131\t    writeFileSync(path, JSON.stringify({ stats: session.stats(), events: session.events }, null, 2));\n132\t    return path;\n133\t  }\n134\t}\n135\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f21d2fda-94ab-442d-8f32-017580283d3b","uuid":"f5d23f62-c115-4e58-9a1e-16f2b1c958be","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:53:17.047Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/harness/lib/report.mjs","content":"/**\n * Scenario report builder — turns a run into the \"Actual results\" table that gets pasted back\n * into the scenario's markdown file, so every run is reproducible and reviewable.\n *\n * A scenario is a list of steps; each step has an EXPECTED outcome declared up front and an\n * ACTUAL outcome recorded at run time. `check()` records a pass/fail against an expectation;\n * `note()` records an observation. Nothing throws by default — a scenario is meant to run to the\n * end and report every failure, not die on the first one.\n */\nimport { mkdirSync, writeFileSync } from 'node:fs';\nimport { dirname } from 'node:path';\n\nexport class Report {\n  constructor(id, title) {\n    this.id = id;\n    this.title = title;\n    this.started = Date.now();\n    this.steps = [];\n    this.current = null;\n    this.metrics = [];\n    this.issues = [];\n  }\n\n  /** Begin a step. `expected` is the contract this step is asserting. */\n  step(name, expected) {\n    this.current = { name, expected, checks: [], notes: [], started: Date.now() };\n    this.steps.push(this.current);\n    console.log(`\\n── ${this.id} · ${name}\\n   expect: ${expected}`);\n    return this.current;\n  }\n\n  check(label, pass, actual = '') {\n    const rec = { label, pass: !!pass, actual: String(actual).slice(0, 500) };\n    (this.current?.checks ?? (this.current = this.step('(unnamed)', '')).checks).push(rec);\n    console.log(`   ${pass ? '✓' : '✗'} ${label}${actual ? ` — ${String(actual).slice(0, 160)}` : ''}`);\n    return rec.pass;\n  }\n\n  note(text) {\n    this.current?.notes.push(String(text));\n    console.log(`   · ${text}`);\n  }\n\n  /** A row for the performance table (turn timings, token burn, event counts). */\n  metric(name, value, unit = '') {\n    this.metrics.push({ name, value, unit });\n    console.log(`   ▸ ${name}: ${value}${unit}`);\n  }\n\n  /** A bug found during the run. `fix` is filled in once the subagent has fixed it. */\n  issue(title, detail, { severity = 'bug', fix = null } = {}) {\n    this.issues.push({ title, detail: String(detail).slice(0, 2000), severity, fix });\n    console.log(`   ⚠ ISSUE [${severity}] ${title}`);\n  }\n\n  get passed() {\n    return this.steps.every((s) => s.checks.every((c) => c.pass));\n  }\n\n  /**\n   * Did the step CURRENTLY being recorded pass?\n   *\n   * `passed` is the whole report; an Act's checkpoint must record the ACT. Writing\n   * `cp.acts.VIII = { passed: report.passed }` after a batch where Act VII failed marked Act VIII\n   * failed too — all three of its checks were green. A checkpoint that lies about which Act broke\n   * is worse than no checkpoint: the next run re-debugs the wrong Act.\n   */\n  get stepPassed() {\n    return (this.current?.checks ?? []).every((c) => c.pass);\n  }\n\n  summary() {\n    const all = this.steps.flatMap((s) => s.checks);\n    return { total: all.length, passed: all.filter((c) => c.pass).length, issues: this.issues.length };\n  }\n\n  /** Render the \"Actual results\" markdown that gets appended to the scenario doc. */\n  markdown() {\n    const s = this.summary();\n    const mins = ((Date.now() - this.started) / 60_000).toFixed(1);\n    const L = [\n      `## Actual results — run ${new Date(this.started).toISOString()}`,\n      ``,\n      `**Verdict: ${this.passed ? '✅ PASS' : '❌ FAIL'}** · ${s.passed}/${s.total} checks · ` +\n        `${s.issues} issue(s) found · ${mins} min wall clock`,\n      ``,\n    ];\n    for (const st of this.steps) {\n      L.push(`### ${st.name}`, ``, `*Expected:* ${st.expected}`, ``);\n      if (st.checks.length) {\n        L.push(`| Check | Result | Actual |`, `|---|---|---|`);\n        for (const c of st.checks) {\n          const actual = c.actual.replace(/\\|/g, '\\\\|').replace(/\\n/g, ' ');\n          L.push(`| ${c.label} | ${c.pass ? '✅' : '❌'} | ${actual || '—'} |`);\n        }\n        L.push('');\n      }\n      for (const n of st.notes) L.push(`> ${n.replace(/\\n/g, '\\n> ')}`, '');\n    }\n    if (this.metrics.length) {\n      L.push(`### Performance`, ``, `| Metric | Value |`, `|---|---|`);\n      for (const m of this.metrics) L.push(`| ${m.name} | ${m.value}${m.unit} |`);\n      L.push('');\n    }\n    if (this.issues.length) {\n      L.push(`### Issues found`, ``);\n      for (const i of this.issues) {\n        L.push(\n          `#### ${i.severity}: ${i.title}`,\n          ``,\n          i.detail,\n          ``,\n          i.fix ? `**Fix:** ${i.fix}` : `**Fix:** _pending_`,\n          ``,\n        );\n      }\n    }\n    return L.join('\\n');\n  }\n\n  save(path) {\n    mkdirSync(dirname(path), { recursive: true });\n    writeFileSync(path, this.markdown());\n    console.log(`\\n📄 ${path}  (${this.passed ? 'PASS' : 'FAIL'})`);\n    return path;\n  }\n\n  /** Dump the raw trace for post-mortems — a scenario report is only as good as its evidence. */\n  saveTrace(path, session) {\n    mkdirSync(dirname(path), { recursive: true });\n    writeFileSync(path, JSON.stringify({ stats: session.stats(), events: session.events }, null, 2));\n    return path;\n  }\n}\n","numLines":135,"startLine":1,"totalLines":135}}}
